m|accessdate=September 1, 2016|date=September 1, 2016}}</ref> || [[Ottawa Senators]] || [[Calder Memorial Trophy]] winner, over 1,000 games played\n|-\n|[[Shawn Horcoff]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/sports/hockey/nhl/edmonton-oilers/edmonton-oilers-shawn-horcoff-retires-detroit-red-wings|title=Ex-Edmonton Oilers captain Shawn Horcoff retires, joins Detroit Red Wings as head of player development - Edmonton Journal|first1=Jim Matheson Updated|last1=September 16|last2=2016|date=17 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref> || [[Anaheim Ducks]] || Over 1,000 games played\n|-\n|[[Barret Jackman]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stlouisgametime.com/2016/10/3/13148494/barret-jackman-to-announce-retirement-at-scottrade-tuesday|title=Barret Jackman To Announce Retirement At Scottrade Tuesday|last=hildymac|date=3 October 2016|website=St. Louis Game Time}}</ref> || [[Nashville Predators]] || Calder Memorial Trophy winner\n|-\n|[[Vincent Lecavalier]]<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/m/sports/hockey/nhl/vincent-lecavalier-retires-1.3645600 Vincent Lecavalier retires after 17 NHL seasons]</ref> || [[Los Angeles Kings]] || [[Maurice \"Rocket\" Richard Trophy]] winner, [[King Clancy Memorial Trophy]] winner, over 1,200 games played\n|-\n|[[David Legwand]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhlpa.com/news/1-11950/david-legwand-retires-after-16-nhl-seasons|title=David Legwand retires after 16 NHL seasons|website=www.nhlpa.com}}</ref> || [[Buffalo Sabres]] || Over 1,100 games played\n|-\n|[[Brad Richards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhlpa.com/news/1-12076/brad-richards-retires-from-nhl-after-15-seasons|title=BRAD RICHARDS RETIRES FROM NHL AFTER 15 SEASONS|website=www.nhlpa.com}}</ref> || [[Detroit Red Wings]] || [[Lady Byng Memorial Trophy]] winner, [[Conn Smythe Trophy]] winner, over 1,100 games played\n|-\n|[[Alex Tanguay]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/alex-tanguay-joins-nhl-network-as-studio-analyst/c-286816378|title=Alex Tanguay joins NHL Network as studio analyst|website=NHL.com}}</ref> || [[Arizona Coyotes]] || Over 1,000 games played\n|-\n|[[Dainius Zubrus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Paskelbtas ledo ritulio rinktin\u0117s kandidat\u0173 s\u0105ra\u0161as: yra ir Dainius Zubrus|url=http://sportas.lrytas.lt/startai/paskelbtas-ledo-ritulio-rinktines-kandidatu-sarasas-yra-ir-dainius-zubrus.htm|website=lrytas.lt|accessdate=12 April 2017|language=lt-LT|date=28 February 2017}}</ref> || [[San Jose Sharks]] || Over 1,200 games played\n|}\n\n===Major milestones reached===\n*On November 21, 2015, [[San Jose Sharks]] forward [[Patrick Marleau]] scored his 1,000th career point, becoming the 83rd player in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patrick Marleau gets 1,00th career point and Sharks beat Penguins 3-1|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/patrick-marleau-gets-1000th-career-point-and-sharks-beat-penguins-3-1/c-789009|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On November 27, 2015, [[Arizona Coyotes]] coach [[Dave Tippett]] won his 500th game, becoming the 22nd coach in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vest|first1=Dave|title='Yotes Notes: Players Give Tippet MVP Belt After 500th Win|url=http://coyotes.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=789991|website=Coyotes.NHL.com|publisher=Arizona Coyotes|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On December 19, 2015, [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] forward [[Phil Kessel]] played his 500th consecutive game, becoming the 23rd player in league history to reach this milestone.\n*On January 4, 2016, [[Colorado Avalanche]] forward [[Jarome Iginla]] scored his 600th NHL goal, becoming the 19th player in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sadowski|first1=Rick|title=Jarome Iginla scores 600th NHL goal, 19th to do so|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/jarome-iginla-scores-600th-nhl-goal-19th-to-do-so/c-795968|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On January 10, 2016, [[Washington Capitals]] forward [[Alexander Ovechkin]] scored his 500th NHL goal, becoming the 43rd player in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Capitals' Ovechkin scores 500th NHL goal|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/capitals-ovechkin-scores-500th-nhl-goal/c-797019|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On January 14, 2016, [[Chicago Blackhawks]] coach [[Joel Quenneville]] won his 783rd game, surpassing [[Al Arbour]] to become the second winningest coach in league history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blackhawks' Quenneville passes Arbour on wins list|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/blackhawks-quenneville-passes-arbour-on-wins-list/c-797784|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On January 21, 2016, [[Vancouver Canucks]] forward [[Daniel Sedin]] scored his 347th NHL goal, surpassing [[Markus N\u00e4slund|Markus Naslund]] for most goals in franchise history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daniel Sedin passes Markus Naslund for most goals in Canucks history|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/daniel-sedin-passes-markus-naslund-for-most-goals-in-canucks-history/|website=Sportsnet.ca|publisher=Rogers Media|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On January 26, 2016, [[San Jose Sharks]] forward [[Joe Thornton]] scored his 1,300th career point, becoming the 33rd player in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sharks' Thornton gets 1,300th NHL point|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/sharks-thornton-gets-1300th-nhl-point/c-799790|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On February 4, 2016, [[Florida Panthers]] forward [[Jarom\u00edr J\u00e1gr|Jaromir Jagr]] scored his 1,100th career assist, becoming the sixth player in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jagr becomes sixth player to reach 1,100 assists|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/jaromir-jagr-1100-assist-panthers/c-278330114?tid=277897704|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On February 13, 2016, [[Boston Bruins]] coach [[Claude Julien (ice hockey)|Claude Julien]] won his 500th game, becoming the 23rd coach in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bruins coach Julien wins 500th NHL game|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/claude-julien-wins-500th-nhl-game/c-278789576?tid=278482306|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On February 20, 2016, [[Florida Panthers]] forward [[Jarom\u00edr J\u00e1gr|Jaromir Jagr]] scored his 742nd career goal, surpassing [[Brett Hull]] to become third in career goals.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gretz|first1=Adam|title=Jaromir Jagr passes Brett Hull for 3rd on NHL all-time goal list|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/eye-on-hockey/25490222/watch-jaromir-jagr-ties-brett-hull-for-3rd-on-nhl-all-time-goal-list|website=CBSSports.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On March 7, 2016, [[Florida Panthers]] forward [[Jarom\u00edr J\u00e1gr|Jaromir Jagr]] scored his 1,851st career point, surpassing [[Gordie Howe]] to become third in career points.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Poupart|first1=Alain|title=Jagr passes Howe on points list|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/jaromir-jagr-gordie-howe-third-nhl-points-list/c-279439158?tid=279372386|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On March 14, 2016, [[Los Angeles Kings]] goaltender [[Jonathan Quick]] recorded his 41st career shutout, surpassing both [[Frank Brimsek]] and [[John Vanbiesbrouck]] to become the all-time shutout leader for U.S.-born goaltenders.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dillman|first1=Lisa|title=Jonathan Quick makes history as Kings blank Blackhawks, 5-0|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/kings/la-sp-kings-blackhawks-20160315-story.html|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=14 March 2016|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref>\n*On April 2, 2016, [[Dallas Stars]] coach [[Lindy Ruff]] won his 700th game, becoming the fifth coach in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dallas Stars at Los Angeles Kings |url=https://www.nhl.com/gamecenter/dal-vs-lak/2016/04/02/2015021169#game=2015021169,game_state=final |website=NHL.com |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n*For the first time in the history of the NHL, Canadian-born players do not comprise a majority the league's players. Of the 680 players who appeared in games over the course of the first two weeks of the season, 49.7 percent were born in Canada, while 24.2 percent were American-born. A record 9.1 percent were from Sweden, and 4.5 percent from Russia.<ref name=\"Canadian-born not the league's majority\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/canadians-do-not-make-up-the-majority-of-nhl-players-this-season-1.380861|title=Canadians do not make up the majority of NHL players this season|last=Seravalli|first=Frank|website=TSN.ca|publisher=Bell Media|date=October 22, 2015|accessdate=October 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Uniforms==\n*The [[Anaheim Ducks]] made a minor change to their home jersey. They changed the collar laces from black to white.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nhl/story/_/id/13765035/2015-16-nhl-season-preview-uni-watch-uniform-changes-tweaks-alternates-throwbacks |title=2015-16 Uni Watch NHL preview |date=October 2, 2015 |accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref> The team also unveiled their new third jersey; the jersey shows a modern Ducks re-colouring of the old Mighty Ducks of Anaheim logo used from the 1993-94 season to the 2005\u201306 season. The jersey is primarily orange with black and bronze striping. On both shoulders it features the team's current primary logo and on one side of the collar it features the team's wordmark \"ANAHEIM\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sportslogos.net/2015/09/07/nhl-shop-leaks-ducks-avalanche-third-jerseys/|title=NHL Shop Leaks Ducks, Avalanche Third Jerseys |date=September 7, 2015 |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> \n*The [[Arizona Coyotes]] began using new home and away jerseys. The primary logo stays the same. The jerseys have added a large black stripe on each arm running from just below the shoulder to the elbow. From there it is red-white-red before it runs white right to the cuff. There's a single hem stripe, black on homes and red on the whites. The home red features a new shoulder patch, a beige/sand coyote paw print with a black \"A\" on it. The road white features a modernized \"AZ/map\" patch, with the font updated to match the new team wordmark. The pants are black, socks are red, black and white similar to the striping on each arm. The new home and away jerseys replace the home and away jerseys that the Coyotes unveiled last year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://coyotes.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=772384| title=Coyotes Reveal New Uniforms at NHL Draft Party | date=June 26, 2015 | accessdate=June 27, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Boston Bruins]] unveiled their new 2016 NHL Winter Classic uniform. The jersey is based on their jersey they wore during the 1924-25 season. The colors have been modernized as black is the primary color, gold and brown as the secondary colors. Two gold horizontal stripes are on each arm and one across the waist. The \"Boston\" wordmark arched over an illustrated bear and Bruins, the crest varies only slightly in the layout from the 1924-25 original. The crest colors celebrate both the beginning and modern day color palette of this historic franchise, and are executed in felt and chenille materials, similar to the original crest. The numbers are in your standard jersey semi-serif block lettering, names and numbers are in white or cream. The numbers on the sleeves are located between the two gold horizontal stripes. The 2016 Winter Classic logo appears on one shoulder as a patch.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bruins.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=784609| title=Bruins Unveil 2016 Bridgestone NHL Winter Classic Uniform | date=October 24, 2015 | accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Buffalo Sabres]] have scrapped their alternate jersey that was unveiled for the 2013-14 season.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sabres.buffalonews.com/2015/03/12/sabres-shelving-reviled-alternate-jersey/| title=Sabres shelving reviled alternate jersey| date=June 23, 2015| accessdate=October 2, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003174024/http://sabres.buffalonews.com/2015/03/12/sabres-shelving-reviled-alternate-jersey/| archive-date=October 3, 2015| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> In lieu of a third jersey, with special permission from the league, the team will wear their white away jerseys for six home games in this season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vogl|first=John|title=Quick hits: Sabres 4, Capitals 1|url=http://sabres.buffalonews.com/2016/01/16/quick-hits-sabres-capitals/|accessdate=January 16, 2016|work=[[The Buffalo News]]|publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|date=January 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160118195615/http://sabres.buffalonews.com/2016/01/16/quick-hits-sabres-capitals/|archive-date=2016-01-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*The [[Chicago Blackhawks]] unveiled a unique jersey for their 2016 NHL Stadium Series game. This jersey is primarily white with black/red/black stripes on the sleeves and socks. The current logo is on the chest. Framed between the two black stripes and over the red stripe on the sleeve is the  familiar \"C\" with crossed tomahawks. The collar of the jersey features two different colors. The four, six-pointed red stars from the [[Flag of Chicago]] is featured on the white portion of the collar, while the other side of the collar is black. Sleeve numbers have been shifted to the shoulders and enlarged. With the shoulders being black, the numbering is white. But, the numbering and lettering on the back is also enlarged and black in color.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sportslogos.net/2015/11/24/blackhawks-unveil-stadium-series-jersey/|title=Blackhawks, Wild Unveil Stadium Series Jerseys|work=sportslogos|accessdate=2015-11-28}}</ref>\n*The [[Colorado Avalanche]] will replace their \"Sasquatch\" alternate logo by a re-coloured \"CO\" from the State of Colorado flag.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.sportslogos.net/2015/06/26/20648/| title=Avalanche Tweak Uniform| date=June 26, 2015 | accessdate=August 4, 2015}}</ref> A new third jersey features the logo of the long-departed [[Colorado Rockies (NHL)|Colorado Rockies]], set in Avalanche colors and number font. In addition to that, they're marking their 20th anniversary with a patch on the front of their jerseys.\n*The Avalanche will also wear a special jersey, which will be primarily white with black, red and blue also featured for the 2016 NHL Stadium Series. It incorporates the same Colorado 'C' design that was added to the Avalanche jersey designs earlier this year. It also features larger numbers on the back and on the shoulders. The collar features a \"5280\" call out, referencing the Avalanche's home in the Mile-High City.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://avalanche.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=779906| title=Avs reveal Coors Light NHL Stadium Series sweater | date=September 21, 2015 | accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Columbus Blue Jackets]] altered their home and road jerseys slightly. The blue Union Army cap shoulder patch worn from the 2003\u201304 season until the 2014\u201315 season was replaced with a new shoulder patch logo. The new shoulder patch logo features the [[Field artillery in the American Civil War#12-pounder Napoleon|1857 Napoleon]] [[cannon]]. It is very similar to the club's current third jersey logo, with the only difference is that the logo features the club's primary colors \u2013 Navy Blue, Red, Silver and White.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bluejackets.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=772327| title=Blue Jackets unveil new secondary mark to be worn as shoulder patch | date=June 26, 2015 | accessdate=June 27, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Detroit Red Wings]] unveiled a unique jersey for their 2016 NHL Stadium Series game. This jersey is primarily red with a diagonal white stripe across the chest. Featured inside the diagonal white stripe is the large red redesigned \"D\" logo. The current Red Wings logo is featured on one shoulder and the 2016 Stadium Series logo is featured on the other shoulder. The word \"EST 1926\" is written on the inside rear collar and the word \"RED WINGS\" is written on one side of the front collar. The jersey also features large numbers on the back and on the shoulder as well as a nameplate featuring arched lettering which is all white in color.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://redwings.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=789249| title=Red Wings unveil Stadium Series jersey | date=November 23, 2015 | accessdate=November 29, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Edmonton Oilers]] unveiled a new alternate jersey. This new throwback jersey is a remake of the jersey worn by the franchise during their inaugural season as the Alberta Oilers of the [[World Hockey Association]]. The jersey is orange with blue and white shoulders and blue/white/blue stripes on the sleeves. The numbers are in the same location as the original WHA jersey on which they are based.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://oilers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=772311| title=Edmonton Oilers Unveil Orange Jersey | date=June 26, 2015 | accessdate=June 28, 2015}}</ref>  \n*The [[Minnesota Wild]] unveiled a unique jersey for their 2016 NHL Stadium Series game. This jersey is primarily green with red and beige stripes on the sleeves. Beige is also featured on the shoulders. The current logo is on the chest. On the left shoulder is their \"State of Hockey\" logo and on the right shoulder is the 2016 Stadium Series logo. The numbering and lettering which are beige in color are enlarged on the sleeve and on the back of the jersey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sportslogos.net/2015/11/24/blackhawks-unveil-stadium-series-jersey/ |title=Blackhawks, Wild Unveil Stadium Series Jerseys |date=November 24, 2015 |accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref> \n*The [[Montreal Canadiens]] made some slight alterations to their home and away jerseys. Four brass hexagonal eyelets and white laces will be reintroduced around the collar, which will also revert to pure white in color. On the team's red home jersey, the French \"LNH\" logo will be stitched at the nape of the neck, and the lone exception to the English \"NHL\" on the away jersey. It is very similar to the club's home and away jerseys worn from the 1970\u201371 season to the 1974\u201375 season. The new home and away jerseys replace the home and away jerseys worn from the 2007\u201308 season until the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://canadiens.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=771966&navid=DL%7CMTL%7Chome |title=Montreal Canadiens unveil new 2015\u201316 jersey |date=June 26, 2015 |accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Montreal Canadiens]] unveiled their 2016 NHL Winter Classic jerseys. The chest stripe is a shade of blue. The \"C\" is white and the \"H\" is red, as they were in 1923-24. An image of the globe is on the sleeves that closely resembles the 1925 version. The French \"LNH\" logo will be stitched near the collar. Other features included into the design are a red collar, red letters, red numbers and red stripes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://canadiens.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=786640 |title=Montreal Canadiens unveil jersey for 2016 Bridgestone NHL Winter Classic |date=November 6, 2015 |accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref> \n*The [[Nashville Predators]] added the 2016 NHL All-Star Game logo as their patch on the front of their jerseys.  They hosted it on January 31, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lukas|first=Paul|title=2015-16 Uni Watch NHL preview|url=http://espn.go.com/nhl/story/_/id/13765035/2015-16-nhl-season-preview-uni-watch-uniform-changes-tweaks-alternates-throwbacks|website=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=October 2, 2015|date=October 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Nashville Predators]] normally wear blue helmets with their gold home jerseys, but this season they'll switch to gold helmets for Saturday home games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://predators.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=776717 |title=Nashville Predators Launch \"Golden Saturdays\" During 2015-16 Season |date=June 26, 2015 |accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[New York Islanders]] unveiled a new alternate jersey. This New Jersey is in black with white trim, with blue and orange relegated to the back collar. The \"NY\" wordmark from the Stadium Series thirds was moved to the new alternates, sans the chrome accents. The new third jersey replaces the Stadium Series third jerseys the Islanders wore in the 2014\u201315 season.<ref name=\"Islanders Unveil New Third Jersey\">{{cite web |url=http://islanders.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=779255 |title=Islanders Unveil New Third Jersey|date=September 16, 2015 |accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[New York Islanders]] added a patch on the right shoulder of the jerseys commemorating their first season in Brooklyn.<ref name=\"Islanders Unveil New Third Jersey\"/> In addition to that, they have also added a left shoulder \"Al\" patch in memory of former coach [[Al Arbour]] who died on August 28, 2015, at the age of 82.<ref name=\"Islanders Unveil New Third Jersey\"/>\n*The [[San Jose Sharks]]  added a 25th anniversary patch. The patch features a new, \"swimming\" Shark with an exposed tail hovering above a diamond-encrusted \"25\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Sharks unveil new logos, commemorative patches for 25th anniversary season|url=http://blogs.mercurynews.com/sharks/2015/06/29/sharks-unveil-new-logos-commemorative-patches-for-25th-anniversary-season/?doing_wp_cron=1435599481.1435539722442626953125|accessdate=June 29, 2015|work=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|publisher=[[Digital First Media]]|date=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[San Jose Sharks]] unveiled their \"heritage jersey.\" This design is identical to the road jerseys worn from 1991-92 season through 1997-98 season, adapted to the [[Reebok Edge]] uniform system.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sharks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=778847| title= Sharks Unveil Heritage Jersey | date=September 12, 2015 | accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref> \n*The [[Washington Capitals]] added a new alternate jersey to their lineup. The primary color for the uniform is red and closely resembles the team's jersey worn from 1974\u201375 season through 1994\u201395 season. The original Capitals wordmark is featured on the front of the jersey with six stars above it and five stars beneath the numbers on each sleeve. The Capitals will wear blue pants and red helmets with their third jerseys. The new third jersey replaces the white third jersey the Capitals wore from the 2011\u201312 season to the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://capitalstoday.monumentalnetwork.com/2015/06/23/capitals-unveil-new-third-jersey-for-2015-16| title=Capitals unveil new third jersey for 2015\u201316 | date=June 23, 2015 | accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2015\u201316 NHL transactions]]\n*[[2015\u201316 NHL suspensions and fines]]\n*[[List of 2015\u201316 NHL Three Star Awards|2015\u201316 NHL Three Star Awards]]\n*[[2016 Stanley Cup playoffs|2016 NHL playoffs]]\n*[[2015 in sports]]\n*[[2016 in sports]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nhl.com/ice/schedulebyseason.htm?season=20152016&gameType=2&team=&network=&venue= 2015\u201316 NHL season Schedule]\n\n{{NHL seasons|2015}}\n{{2015\u201316 NHL season by team}}\n{{2015\u201316 in men's ice hockey}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2015-16 Nhl season}}\n[[Category:2015\u201316 NHL season| ]]\n[[Category:2015\u201316 in American ice hockey by league|1]]\n[[Category:2015\u201316 in Canadian ice hockey by league|1]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|National Hockey League season}}\n{{Infobox sports season\n| title = 2015\u201316 NHL season\n| league = [[National Hockey League]]\n| sport = [[Ice hockey]]\n| duration = October 7, 2015 \u2013 June 12, 2016\n| no_of_games = 82 \n| no_of_teams = 30\n| attendance =\n| draft = Draft\n| draft_link = 2015 NHL Entry Draft\n| top_pick_link = List of first overall NHL draft picks\n| top_pick = [[Connor McDavid]] \n| picked_by = [[Edmonton Oilers]]\n| season = Regular season\n| season_champ_name = [[Presidents' Trophy]]\n| season_champs = [[Washington Capitals]]\n| MVP = [[Patrick Kane]] <small>([[Chicago Blackhawks|Blackhawks]])</small> \n| MVP_link = Hart Memorial Trophy\n| top_scorer = Patrick Kane <small>(Blackhawks)</small>\n| top_scorer_link = Art Ross Trophy\n| playoffs = Playoffs\n| playoffs_link = 2016 Stanley Cup playoffs\n| conf1 = Eastern\n| conf1_link = Eastern Conference (NHL)\n| conf1_champ = [[Pittsburgh Penguins]]\n| conf1_runner-up = [[Tampa Bay Lightning]]\n| conf2 = Western\n| conf2_link = Western Conference (NHL)\n| conf2_champ = [[San Jose Sharks]]\n| conf2_runner-up = [[St. Louis Blues]]\n| finals = Stanley Cup \n| finals_link = 2016 Stanley Cup Finals\n| finals_champ = [[Pittsburgh Penguins]]\n| finals_runner-up = [[San Jose Sharks]]\n| finals_MVP = [[Sidney Crosby]] <small>([[Pittsburgh Penguins|Penguins]])</small>\n| finals_mvp_name = [[Conn Smythe Trophy]]\n| playoffs_MVP_link =\n| nextseason_year = [[2016\u201317 NHL season|2016\u201317]]\n| prevseason_year = [[2014\u201315 NHL season|2014\u201315]]\n| seasonslist      = List of NHL seasons\n| seasonslistnames = NHL\n}}\nThe '''2015\u201316 NHL season''' was the [[List of NHL seasons|99th season]] of operation (98th season of play) of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). Thirty teams competed in 82-game regular season schedules from October 7, 2015 to April 10, 2016.\n\nThe [[2016 Stanley Cup playoffs]] following the regular season began on April 13 and ended June 12 with the Pittsburgh Penguins winning their fourth Stanley Cup. None of the seven Canadian-based teams qualified for the playoffs; this was the second season in league history that the playoff field consisted of only United States-based teams. The only other time in league history that no Canadian teams qualified for the postseason was in [[1970 Stanley Cup playoffs|1970]].<ref name=star-cadrought>{{cite news|first=Aleksandra|last=Sagan|title=Canadian NHL playoff drought could be 'massive hit' to Rogers|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/02/24/canadian-nhl-playoff-drought-could-be-massive-hit-to-rogers.html|work=Canadian Press|publisher=Toronto Star|date=February 24, 2016|accessdate=March 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Dave|last=Stubbs|title=Woe Canada. No playoffs this year north of border|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/no-canadian-nhl-teams-in-stanley-cup-playoffs/c-279984346|publisher=NHL|date=March 31, 2016|accessdate=June 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==League business==\n\n===Salary cap===\nIn December 2014, commissioner [[Gary Bettman]] told teams that he projected the [[NHL salary cap|salary cap]] to increase to at least $73 million for the 2015\u201316 season, citing the fluctuating value of the [[Canadian dollar]].<ref name=nhl-salarycapchange>{{cite web|title=Bettman: Salary-cap projection for '15\u201316 around $73M, but, it only went up to $71.2m|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=743047|website=NHL.com|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref> The cap was ultimately set at $71.4 million.<ref name=nhlcom-toughreality>{{cite web|title=Toews, Blackhawks face tough reality of salary cap|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=771813|website=NHL.com|accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Rule changes===\nRule changes approved by the NHL Board of Governors on June 24, 2015, include:<ref name=\"NHLRuleChanges\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=771976 | title=Board of Governors approves 2015\u201316 rules changes | website=NHL.com | date=June 26, 2015 | accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n* '''3-on-3 overtime''': Overtime during the regular season will now have three skaters per side, instead of the 4-on-4 overtime system that had been used since [[1999-2000 NHL season|1999\u20132000]].<ref name=\"Yahoo20150317\">{{cite web|last=Cotsonika|first=Nicholas|title=NHL GMs approve 3-on-3 overtime, but what format?|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nhl-puck-daddy/nhl-gms-approve-3-on-3-overtime--but-what-format--183117113.html|website=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|accessdate=June 24, 2015|location=[[Boca Raton, Florida]]|date=March 17, 2015}}</ref> However, if there are carry-over penalties from the third period to overtime, a side is still guaranteed to have at least three skaters and the man-advantage will be adjusted accordingly (e.g. a 5-on-4 power play at the end of regulation will be converted to a 4-on-3 one at the start of overtime).<ref name=\"NHLRuleChanges\"/> The Board of Governors implemented 3-on-3 overtime to help decrease shootouts.<ref name=\"Yahoo20150317\"/> [[Jason Garrison]] of the [[Tampa Bay Lightning]] scored the first 3-on-3 overtime goal on October 9, 2015 for a 3-2 victory over the [[Philadelphia Flyers]]. \n* '''Expanded video review with coach's challenge''': Video review has been expanded to include a coach's challenge, similar to the system used by the [[National Football League|NFL]] since [[1999 NFL season#Major rule changes|1999]]:<ref name=\"NHLRuleChanges\"/>\n** Like the NFL, each challenge will require the use of a team's timeout. If the challenge is successful, the timeout is restored.\n** Teams may only challenge the following situations:\n*** Whether a goal called on the ice should have been disallowed because the attacking team was offside or interfered with the goaltender;\n*** Whether a disallowed goal, called on grounds of goalkeeper interference, should instead be overturned because either:\n**** there was no actual contact between the attacking player and the goalie\n**** the attacking player was actually pushed or fouled by a defender into the goalie\n**** the attacking player's position in the crease did not actually impair or impact the goalie's play\n** Inside the final minute of regulation, and during overtime, all reviews that would otherwise be subject to the coach's challenge will instead be initiated by the NHL's Situation Room in Toronto\n** All reviews that are subject to the coach's challenge will be conducted by the on-ice officials on an ice-level [[Tablet computer|tablet monitor]] instead of the Situation Room.\n** All reviews involving whether the puck entered the net will still be initiated by the Situation Room.<ref name=\"NHLRuleChanges\"/>\n* '''New faceoff rule''': During faceoffs not at center-ice, the player who is on the defensive side of the red line will now be required to put his stick down first.<ref name=\"NHLRuleChanges\"/> For faceoffs at the center-ice dot, the visiting player will still be the first one to place down his stick. This rule change, giving the attacking team a slight advantage during faceoffs (as opposed to giving this advantage to the home team all the time), is intended to help increase puck-possession time and potentially more goals.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web | url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=758665 | title=GMs propose new faceoff rule to increase offense | website=NHL.com | date=March 18, 2015 | accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Expansion bids===\n{{main|Potential National Hockey League expansion}}\n\nFor the second time since 2000, the league ended a moratorium on potential [[expansion team]]s and began accepting bids for potential expansion teams that, if approved, would begin play in the 2017\u201318 season. During the 2015 offseason, two ownership groups offered bids: [[Quebecor]], which planned on reviving the [[Quebec Nordiques]] at a [[Videotron Centre|new arena]] in [[Quebec City|Quebec City, Quebec]], and Bill Foley's Black Knight Sports & Entertainment, which intended to place [[Vegas Golden Knights|an expansion team]] at a [[T-Mobile Arena|new arena]] in [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]]. The league concluded the vetting process on September 4, 2015, with a final decision to follow in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooper|first=Josh|title=Las Vegas and Quebec City NHL expansion bids move to 'Phase III'|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nhl-puck-daddy/las-vegas-and-quebec-city-nhl-expansion-bids-move-to--phase-iii-220135099.html|website=sports.yahoo.com|publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|accessdate=August 21, 2015|date=August 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Media rights===\nIn August 2015, the league announced a six-year deal with [[MLB Advanced Media]] (MLBAM) to take over the technical operations of the NHL's in-house digital properties. Under the agreement, MLBAM took over the operations of the NHL's websites, apps, streaming services, and other digital properties starting in January 2016. MLBAM also took over international distribution of the league's digital out-of-market streaming services outside of Canada and Scandinavia.<ref name=\"wsj-mblam\"/> The NHL also took an equity stake of up to 10 percent in BAM Tech, a spin-off of MLBAM's streaming media business.<ref name=\"wsj-mblam\">{{cite news|last=Ramachandran|first=Shalini|title=MLB's Tech Unit Wins NHL Streaming Business|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mlbs-tech-unit-wins-nhl-streaming-business-1438715135|accessdate=August 4, 2015|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp]]|date=August 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/8/4/9090897/mlb-bam-live-streaming-internet-tv-nhl-hbo-now-espn|title=How baseball's tech team built the future of television|author=Ben Popper|publisher=Vox Media|work=The Verge}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A closer look at NHL's partnership with MLBAM|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/a-closer-look-at-nhls-partnership-with-mlbam/|website=Sportsnet.ca|publisher=Rogers Media|accessdate=August 4, 2015}}</ref> As an aspect of the deal, the [[NHL Network (United States)|U.S. version of NHL Network]] was also relocated to the facilities of [[MLB Network]].<ref name=\"wsj-mblam\"/> The [[NHL Network (Canada)|Canadian version of NHL Network]] was shut down August 31, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2015/2015-430.htm|title=Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2015-430|date=2015-09-17|accessdate=2015-09-17|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]}}</ref>\n\nThe re-launch of the league's digital properties under MLBAM occurred in February 2016, with the launch of the new NHL.com website and mobile app following the [[2016 NHL All-Star Game]].<ref name=nhl-nhlredesign>{{cite web|title=NHL, MLBAM unveil details for redesigned platforms|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=799598|website=NHL.com|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> The re-launched NHL GameCenter Live service outside of Canada was re-branded as NHL.tv, while the Canadian service remains branded as Rogers NHL GameCentre Live. Both services were upgraded to utilize a new client on MLBAM architecture with support for 60 [[frames per second|FPS]] streaming.<ref name=\"svg-mlbamgcl\">{{cite web|title=Rogers NHL GameCentre LIVE Delivers New Ways to Watch the Game|url=http://www.sportsvideo.org/2016/02/02/rogers-nhl-gamecentre-live-delivers-new-ways-to-watch-the-game/|website=Sports Video Group|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> The re-launch of the services, however, was marred by technical issues caused by a malfunctioning [[content delivery network]].<ref name=\"yahoo-nhltvdisaster\">{{cite web|title=NHL.tv explains what happened in disastrous launch|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nhl-puck-daddy/nhl-tv-explains-what-happened-in-disastrous-launch-175300060.html|website=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs the result of a lawsuit settlement, the NHL agreed to offer single-team packages for its out-of-market services in the United States.<ref name=sbn-singleteam>{{cite web|title=NHL TV package settlement might feel like win for fans, but it's not even close|url=http://www.broadstreethockey.com/2015/6/15/8783249/nhl-tv-settlement-settlement-game-center-live|website=Broad Street Hockey (SBNation)|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> The updated NHL app also offers a downsized out-of-market subscription service known as NHL Premium, which streams the conclusion of each game (final five minutes, plus overtime/shootouts if needed).<ref name=nhl-nhlredesign/>\n\nIn Canada, the Sunday-night ''Hometown Hockey'' game of the week on [[City (TV network)|City]] was moved to [[NHL on Sportsnet|Sportsnet]].<ref name=gandm-pucksandprofit>{{cite news|title=Pucks and profit: CEO opens up about Rogers' rookie NHL season|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/rogers-hockey-guy-laurence/article24702297/|accessdate=May 31, 2015|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=torsun-rhhmove>{{cite web|title=Rogers moving 'Hometown Hockey' from City to Sportsnet this fall|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/06/02/rogers-moving-hometown-hockey-from-city-to-sportsnet-this-fall|website=Toronto Sun|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> Both [[Sportsnet]] and [[TSN Hockey|TSN]] announced plans to produce telecasts of selected national and regional games in [[4K resolution|4K]] [[ultra high-definition television]].<ref name=gandm-rogers4k>{{cite news|title=Rogers leveraging sports ownership to push 4K TV|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/rogers-leveraging-sports-ownership-to-push-4k-tv/article26672645/|accessdate=6 October 2015|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref><ref name=tsn-4kraptors>{{cite web|title=TSN delivers live 4K broadcast of Raptors-Celtics|url=https://www.tsn.ca/tsn-delivers-live-4k-broadcast-of-raptors-celtics-1.422478|website=TSN.ca|publisher=Bell Media|accessdate=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2016, the NHL announced a deal with [[Yahoo! Sports]], in which it will offer free online streaming in the U.S. of up to four out-of-market games per-week. The site will also feature additional NHL content, such as condensed games and highlight showcases. The deal expands upon an ongoing relationship with U.S. rightsholder NBC, as well as a relationship with Major League Baseball to host the MLB.tv ''Game of the Day'' stream.<ref name=\"thewrap-yahoonhl\">{{cite news|title=Yahoo, NHL Partner to Live-Stream Hockey Games for Free|url=http://www.thewrap.com/yahoo-nhl-partner-to-livestream-hockey-games-for-free/|accessdate=10 March 2016|work=The Wrap}}</ref><ref name=\"adweek-yahoonhl\">{{cite news|title=Yahoo Betting Big on Live Sports With Deal to Stream NHL Games|url=http://www.adweek.com/news/television/yahoo-betting-big-live-sports-deal-stream-nhl-games-170091|accessdate=10 March 2016|work=Adweek}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2016, NBC Sports announced that it would provide national radio broadcasts of the [[2016 Stanley Cup Finals]] via [[NBC Sports Radio]].<ref name=\"sbj-nbcradiosc\">{{cite web|title=NBC Sports Radio Named Terrestrial Partner For '16 Stanley Cup Final|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Morning-Buzz/2016/05/03/radio.aspx|website=Sports Business Journal|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> [[NHL Radio]] broadcasts had not been heard continent-wide since 2008.\n\n=== Change in jersey supplier ===\nOn September 15, 2015, the NHL announced that [[Adidas]] would replace [[Reebok]] as the supplier of all team jerseys beginning in the 2017\u201318 season.<ref name=\"nhl-adidas\">{{cite web|title=Adidas to become official NHL outfitter in 2017-18|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/adidas-to-become-official-nhl-outfitter-in-2017-18/c-779133|website=NHL.com|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching changes==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Coaching changes\n!colspan=\"4\"|Offseason\n|-\n! style=\"width:13%;\"| Team\n! style=\"width:11%;\"| 2014\u201315 coach\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| 2015\u201316 coach\n!Story / Accomplishments\n|-\n| [[Buffalo Sabres]]\n| [[Ted Nolan]]\n| [[Dan Bylsma]]\n| Nolan was fired on April 12, 2015. In his second stint with the club, he compiled a record of 40\u201387\u201317 over the course of 1\u00be seasons, both of which ended with the team in last place in the league.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sabres.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=762979 | title=Nolan relieved of duties as Sabres' head coach | date=April 12, 2015 | accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> On May 28, Bylsma succeeded after serving on the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] from [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2009]] to [[2013\u201314 NHL season|2014]], where he accumulated a 252\u2013117\u201332 regular season record and a 43\u201335 postseason record. In 2009, he guided the Penguins to win the [[2009 Stanley Cup Finals|Stanley Cup]]. For his efforts during the [[2010\u201311 NHL season|2010\u201311 season]], he was awarded the [[Jack Adams Award]] as the league's most outstanding coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/sabres-bylsma-primed-to-win-jack-adams-award/c-780899\n|title=Sabres' Bylsma primed to win Jack Adams Award|date=October 2, 2015|accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Detroit Red Wings]]\n| [[Mike Babcock]] \n| [[Jeff Blashill]]\n| Babcock's contract with the Red Wings was to expire July 1, 2015; the Red Wings granted his request to pursue employment elsewhere on May 8, after failing to come to terms on a contract.<ref name=babcockleaves>{{cite web| url=http://redwings.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=766998 |title=Babcock is free to explore opportunities|first=Bill|last=Roose|work=Detroit Red Wings|date=May 8, 2015|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref> In ten seasons with the Red Wings, Babcock accumulated a record of 458\u2013223\u201315, made the playoffs every year, and won the Stanley Cup in [[2008 Stanley Cup Finals|2008]]. Babcock was highly sought after on the open market, and on May 20, 2015, after several teams courted him, Babcock signed with the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]].<ref name=babcockleafs>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/twitter-reaction-mike-babcock-detroit-red-wings-toronto-maple-leafs-buffalo-sabres-head-coach/|title=\"Twitter reaction: Mike Babcock joins Maple Leafs\", ''Sportnet.ca'', (2015)}}</ref> The Red Wings promoted [[Jeff Blashill]], who coached the Red Wings' minor league affiliate the [[Grand Rapids Griffins]]. Once the Griffins completed their playoff run, the Red Wings retained Blashill's rights and did not allow any NHL team to interview him for openings.<ref name=babcockleaves/>\n|-\n| [[Edmonton Oilers]]\n| [[Dallas Eakins]],<br>[[Todd Nelson (ice hockey)|Todd Nelson]]*\n| [[Todd McLellan]]\n|Eakins, in 1\u00bd seasons with the Oilers, compiled a record of 36\u201363\u201314 and was fired on December 15, 2014. Nelson completed the season with a record of 17\u201325\u20139. On May 19, McLellan succeeded after serving seven seasons as a head coach with the San Jose Sharks, after mutually agreeing to part ways with them on April 20, 2015. In his tenure in San Jose, he became the most successful coach to date and compiled a regular season record of 311\u2013163\u201366. He made the playoffs six out of the seven seasons, compiling a record of 30\u201332.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/todd-mclellan-named-coach-of-edmonton-oilers/c-768182|title=Todd McLellan named coach of Edmonton Oilers|website=NHL.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[New Jersey Devils]]\n| [[Peter DeBoer]],<br>[[Scott Stevens]]*,<br>[[Adam Oates]]*\n| [[John Hynes (ice hockey)|John Hynes]]\n| DeBoer, in 3\u00bd seasons with the Devils, compiled a record of 114\u201393\u201341 before being fired on December 26, 2014. The Devils used interim head coaches Scott Stevens and Adam Oates for the remainder of the season. DeBoer joined the San Jose Sharks. On June 2, 2015, Hynes succeeds after serving on the [[Wilkes-Barre/Scranton Penguins]] of the [[American Hockey League]] as a head coach from 2009 to 2010, where he compiled a 231\u2013126\u201310\u201317. He qualified for the playoffs in all five seasons behind the bench. With this hiring, he became the youngest coach in the NHL at the age of 40.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/devils/news/devils-name-john-hynes-as-head-coach/c-769654|title=Devils name John Hynes as head coach|website=NHL.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Philadelphia Flyers]]\n| [[Craig Berube]]\n| [[Dave Hakstol]]\n| Berube was fired on April 17, 2015, after accumulating a record of 75\u201358\u201328 in two seasons.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://flyers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=763801 | title=Craig Berube relieved of duties as Flyers head coach | date=April 17, 2015 | accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> In his first season, he took the Flyers to the playoffs. They ended up losing to the New York Rangers in the first round 4\u20133. The team missed the playoffs in Berube's second season at the helm. Hakstol, whom the Flyers hired on May 18, 2015, had been head coach of the [[North Dakota Fighting Hawks men's ice hockey|University of North Dakota men's ice hockey]] team for the previous 11 years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Peaslee|first1=Evan|title=Flyers name Dave Hakstol new head coach|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/flyers-name-dave-hakstol-new-head-coach/|website=Sportsnet.ca|publisher=Rogers Media|accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[San Jose Sharks]]\n| [[Todd McLellan]]\n| [[Peter DeBoer]]\n| McLellan was San Jose's most successful coach to date and compiled a regular season record of 311\u2013163\u201366 over seven seasons. However, the San Jose Sharks and Todd McLellan mutually agreed to part ways on April 20, 2015, after failing to make the playoffs for the first time in his tenure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=764211&navid=DL |title=Sharks and McLellan mutually agree to part ways |publisher=NHL |date=April 20, 2015}}</ref> On May 19, 2015, McLellan then became head coach of the Edmonton Oilers. On May 28, 2015, the Sharks announced that they had hired Peter DeBoer. He had been the head coach of the New Jersey Devils, where he left with a 114\u201394\u201341 record over parts of four seasons. In his tenure, he guided the Devils to the [[2012 Stanley Cup Finals]] where they lost in six games to the Los Angeles Kings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/peter-deboer-hired-as-coach-of-san-jose-sharks/c-769154|title=Peter DeBoer hired as coach of San Jose Sharks|website=NHL.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n| [[Randy Carlyle]],<br>[[Peter Horachek]]*\n| [[Mike Babcock]]\n| Carlyle began the season as the head coach, but was fired on January 6, 2015, after posting a 21\u201316\u20133 record through 40 games. In 3\u00bd seasons with the Leafs, he compiled a record of 91\u201378\u201319. Horachek finished the season with a record of 9\u201328\u20135 and was dismissed on April 12, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/maple-leafs-fire-gm-nonis-interim-coach-horachek/|title=\"Maple Leafs fire GM Nonis, interim coach Horachek\", ''Sportsnet.ca'', (2015)}}</ref> On May 20, 2015, the Maple Leafs signed Babcock to an eight-year, US$50,000,000 contract (the largest for a coach in NHL history).<ref name=babcockleafs/> In ten seasons with the Red Wings, Babcock accumulated a record of 458\u2013223\u201315, made the playoffs every year, and won the Stanley Cup in [[2008 Stanley Cup Finals|2008]].\n|-\n|-\n\n!colspan=\"4\"|In-season\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Team\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Outgoing coach\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Incoming coach\n!Story / Accomplishments\n|-\n| [[Columbus Blue Jackets]]\n| [[Todd Richards (ice hockey)|Todd Richards]]\n| [[John Tortorella]]\n| Richards was fired on October 21, 2015, after posting a 0\u20137\u20130 record through 7 games this season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehockeynews.com/blog/blue-jackets-fire-todd-richards-john-tortorella-takes-over-in-columbus/ | title=Blue Jackets fire Todd Richards, John Tortorella takes over in Columbus | date=October 21, 2015 | accessdate=October 21, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151022142410/http://www.thehockeynews.com/blog/blue-jackets-fire-todd-richards-john-tortorella-takes-over-in-columbus/ | archive-date=October 22, 2015 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> He had been named interim head coach on January 9, 2012, before being promoted to the franchise's sixth head coach on May 14, 2012. Richards posted a record of 127\u2013112\u201321 in 260 games. The team made the postseason once under his tenure, going 2\u20134, including the team's first-ever postseason win on April 19, 2014. On October 21, 2015, the Blue Jackets signed Tortorella to become its next head coach.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bluejackets.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=784133 | title=John Tortorella replaces Todd Richards as Blue Jackets head coach | date=October 21, 2015 | accessdate=October 21, 2015}}</ref> He had been the head coach of the Vancouver Canucks (2013\u201314), New York Rangers (2009\u201313), and the Tampa Bay Lightning (2001\u201308). He guided Tampa Bay to the Stanley Cup in [[2004 Stanley Cup Finals|2004]].\n|-\n|[[Pittsburgh Penguins]]\n|[[Mike Johnston (ice hockey)|Mike Johnston]]\n|[[Mike Sullivan (ice hockey)|Mike Sullivan]]\n| Johnston was fired on December 12, 2015, after posting a 15\u201310\u20133 record through 28 games this season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://penguins.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=792317 | title=Mike Sullivan Named Head Coach of Pittsburgh Penguins | date=December 12, 2015 | accessdate=December 12, 2015}}</ref> He had served as the head coach since the start of the 2014\u201315 season. He left with a record of 58\u201337\u201315 in 110 games. The team made the postseason once under his tenure despite going 1\u20134. On December 12, Sullivan who was coaching the [[Wilkes-Barre/Scranton Penguins]] of the [[American Hockey League]] at the time, received the call for the head coaching vacancy with the main club.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://theahl.com/sullivan-promoted-to-pittsburgh-p200587 | title=Sullivan promoted to Pittsburgh | date=December 12, 2015 | accessdate=December 12, 2015}}</ref> He was in his first season with the [[farm team]], taking them to an 18\u20135\u20130\u20130 record. \n|-\n|[[Minnesota Wild]]\n|[[Mike Yeo]]\n|[[John Torchetti]]*\n| Yeo was fired on February 13, 2016, after posting a 23\u201322\u201310 record through 55 games this season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://wild.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=868676| title=Minnesota Wild Head Coach Mike Yeo Relieved Of Coaching Duties | date=February 13, 2016 | accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> He had served as the head coach since the start of the 2011\u201312 season. He left with a record of 173\u2013132\u201344 in 349 games and made the playoffs three times despite going 11\u201317. On February 13, Torchetti who was coaching the [[Iowa Wild]] of the [[American Hockey League]] at the time, became the interim head coach for the main club.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://theahl.com/iowa-s-torchetti-promoted-to-minnesota-p201327| title=iowa-s-torchetti-promoted-to-minnesota-p201327| date=February 13, 2016| accessdate=February 13, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215095222/http://theahl.com/iowa-s-torchetti-promoted-to-minnesota-p201327| archive-date=2016-02-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> In parts of two seasons or 114 games with the [[farm team]], he amassed a record of 36\u201368\u20135\u20135.\n|-\n|}\n\n(*) Indicates interim.\n\n== Arena changes ==\n* The 2015\u201316 season marked the [[New York Islanders]]' move from the [[Nassau Veterans Memorial Coliseum]] in [[Uniondale, New York|Uniondale]] to [[Barclays Center]] in [[Brooklyn]].<ref>{{cite web\n|title=New York Islanders will move to Brooklyn in 2015|first=Adam|last=Gretz|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/blog/eye-on-hockey/20667444/report-islanders-moving-to-brooklyn-in-2015|work=[[CBS Sports]]|date=October 24, 2012|accessdate=October 24, 2012}}</ref>\n* The [[Edmonton Oilers]] played their final season at [[Rexall Place]]. They moved to the newly constructed [[Rogers Place]] in the 2016\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tychkowski|first1=Robert|title=Edmonton Oilers dominate Vancouver Canucks in final game at Rexall Place|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/sports/hockey/nhl/edmonton-oilers/edmonton-oilers-dominate-vancouver-canucks-in-final-game-at-rexall-place|newspaper=Edmonton Journal|accessdate=April 7, 2016|date=April 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Regular season==\nThe regular season began on October 7, 2015, and ended on April 10, 2016. The playoffs began on Wednesday, April 13, 2016.\n\n===Winter Classic===\n{{main|2016 NHL Winter Classic}}\nThe 2016 NHL Winter Classic was held on January 1, 2016. The game, the eighth Winter Classic, saw the [[Montreal Canadiens]] defeat the [[Boston Bruins]], 5\u20131, at [[Gillette Stadium]] in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts|Foxborough]], [[Massachusetts]], a significant event in one of the NHL's [[Bruins\u2013Canadiens rivalry|best-known rivalries]]. A Bruins and Canadiens alumni game was also played on December 31, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bruins, Canadiens alumni rosters revealed for 2016 NHL Winter Classic Alumni Game|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2015/11/24/bruins-canadiens-alumni-rosters-revealed-for-nhl-winter-classic-alumni-game/o3xxEh9OIK5kEakg1VClgM/story.html|accessdate=December 21, 2015|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=November 24, 2015}}</ref> The [[Boston Pride]] [[National Women's Hockey League (2015\u2013)|women's professional hockey]] team [[2015 Women's Winter Classic|played before the alumni game]] against [[Les Canadiennes]] of the [[Canadian Women's Hockey League]] to a 1\u20131 tie in the first ever Women's Winter Classic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/m_news.htm?id=794629|accessdate=December 28, 2015 |title=NHL to host first-ever Outdoor WomhnClassic presented by Scotiabank |website=NHL |date=December 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Stadium Series===\n{{main|2016 NHL Stadium Series}}\n\nThere were two Stadium Series games planned. The first one featured the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] and the [[Minnesota Wild]] at [[TCF Bank Stadium]] on Sunday, February 21, 2016, where the Wild defeated the Blackhawks 6\u20131. The other game was the [[Detroit Red Wings]] and the [[Colorado Avalanche]] at [[Coors Field]] on Saturday, February 27, 2016, where the Red Wings defeated the Avalanche 5\u20133.\n\n===All\u2013Star Game===\n{{main|61st National Hockey League All-Star Game}}\nThe 61st [[National Hockey League All-Star Game]] was held in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] at [[Bridgestone Arena]], home of the [[Nashville Predators]], on January 31, 2016. The All-Star Game adopted a new, three-on-three tournament format; there were three 20-minute games, with four All-Star teams based on the league's four divisions. The Atlantic Division All-Stars faced the Metropolitan Division All-Stars, while the Central Division All-Stars played against the Pacific Division All-Stars. The winners of these two games then met in an ''All-Star Game Final''. Had a tie remained after 20 minutes, then it would have immediately gone to a shootout to determine the winner; there would be no standard overtime.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=788532 | title=New format for Honda NHL All-Star Game announced | publisher=NHL.com | date=November 18, 2015 | accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref> The Pacific Division All-Stars, led by fan-voted captain and MVP [[John Scott (ice hockey)|John Scott]], won the tournament, beating the Atlantic All-Stars in the finals\n\n===Postponed games===\nThree games were postponed due to the [[January 2016 United States blizzard]]: the [[2015\u201316 Anaheim Ducks season|Anaheim Ducks]]\u2013[[2015\u201316 Washington Capitals season|Washington Capitals]] game originally scheduled for January 22, the [[2015\u201316 Philadelphia Flyers season|Philadelphia Flyers]]\u2013[[2015\u201316 New York Islanders season|New York Islanders]] game originally scheduled for January 23, and the [[2015\u201316 Pittsburgh Penguins season|Pittsburgh Penguins]]\u2013Washington Capitals game originally scheduled for January 24.<ref>{{cite news|title=Storm knocks out Sunday's Penguins-Capitals game|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nhl/2016/01/23/storm-knocks-out-sundays-penguins-capitals-game/79223222/|accessdate=January 23, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=January 23, 2016|location=[[New York City]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Storm knocks out Saturday's Flyers-Islanders game|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nhl/2016/01/23/storm-knocks-out-saturdays-flyers-islanders-game/79224548/|accessdate=January 23, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=January 23, 2016|location=[[New York City]]}}</ref>  The Penguins\u2013Capitals game was rescheduled for March 1, while the Ducks\u2013Capitals and Flyers\u2013Islanders games were rescheduled for April 10.<ref>{{cite web|title=NHL announces three rescheduled games|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-announces-three-rescheduled-games/c-278172224|website=nhl.com|publisher=NHL Enterprises, L.P.|accessdate=February 2, 2016|location=[[New York City]]|date=February 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Standings==\n{{2015\u201316 NHL Metropolitan Division standings|table_header=Top 3 ([[Metropolitan Division]])|lowest_pos=3}}\n{{2015\u201316 NHL Atlantic Division standings|table_header=Top 3 ([[Atlantic Division (NHL)|Atlantic Division]])|lowest_pos=3}}\n{{2015\u201316 NHL Eastern Conference Wild Card standings}}\n{{2015\u201316 NHL Central Division standings|table_header=Top 3 ([[Central Division (NHL)|Central Division]])|lowest_pos=3}}\n{{2015\u201316 NHL Pacific Division standings|table_header=Top 3 ([[Pacific Division (NHL)|Pacific Division]])|lowest_pos=3}}\n{{2015\u201316 NHL Western Conference Wild Card standings}}\nTie Breakers:<br>\n1. Fewer number of games played.<br>\n2. Greater Regulation + OT Wins (ROW)<br>\n3. Greatest number of points earned in head-to-head play (If teams played an unequal # of head-to-head games, the result of the first game on the home ice of the team with the extra home game is discarded.)<br>\n4. Greater Goal differential\n\n==Player statistics==\n\n===Scoring leaders===\nThe following players led the league in regular season points at the conclusion of games played on April 10, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhl.com/stats/player?reportType=season&report=skatersummary&season=20152016&gameType=2&sort=points,goals,gamesPlayed&aggregate=0&pos=S |title=Player Stats: 2015\u20132016 Regular season: All Skaters&nbsp;\u2013 Total Points |publisher=National Hockey League }}</ref>\n<!-- IMPORTANT: Rank players by Pts, then G, then GP (fewer) If there is more than 10 players, '''nonetheless list all the leaders''' -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width: 12em;\" | Player\n! style=\"width: 13em;\" | Team\n! style=\"width: 4em;\" | {{abbr|GP|Games Played}}\n! style=\"width: 4em;\" | {{abbr|G|Goals}}\n! style=\"width: 4em;\" | {{abbr|A|Assists}}\n! style=\"width: 4em;\" | {{abbr|Pts|Points}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width: 4em;\" | {{abbr|+/\u2013|Plus/Minus}}\n! style=\"width: 4em;\" | {{abbr|PIM|Penalties In Minutes}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{sortname|Patrick|Kane}} || style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Chicago Blackhawks]] || 82 || 46 || 60 || '''106''' || +17 || 30\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{sortname|Jamie|Benn}} || style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Dallas Stars]] || 82 || 41 || 48 || '''89''' || +7 || 64\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{sortname|Sidney|Crosby}} || style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] || 80 || 36 || 49 || '''85''' || +19 || 42\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{sortname|Joe|Thornton}} || style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[San Jose Sharks]] || 82 || 19 || 63 || '''82''' || +25 || 54\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{sortname|Erik|Karlsson}} || style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Ottawa Senators]] || 82 || 16 || 66 || '''82''' || \u20132 || 50\n|- style=\"text-align