s-detroit-red-wings|title=Ex-Edmonton Oilers captain Shawn Horcoff retires, joins Detroit Red Wings as head of player development - Edmonton Journal|first1=Jim Matheson Updated|last1=September 16|last2=2016|date=17 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref> || [[Anaheim Ducks]] || Over 1,000 games played\n|-\n|[[Barret Jackman]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stlouisgametime.com/2016/10/3/13148494/barret-jackman-to-announce-retirement-at-scottrade-tuesday|title=Barret Jackman To Announce Retirement At Scottrade Tuesday|last=hildymac|date=3 October 2016|website=St. Louis Game Time}}</ref> || [[Nashville Predators]] || Calder Memorial Trophy winner\n|-\n|[[Vincent Lecavalier]]<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/m/sports/hockey/nhl/vincent-lecavalier-retires-1.3645600 Vincent Lecavalier retires after 17 NHL seasons]</ref> || [[Los Angeles Kings]] || [[Maurice \"Rocket\" Richard Trophy]] winner, [[King Clancy Memorial Trophy]] winner, over 1,200 games played\n|-\n|[[David Legwand]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhlpa.com/news/1-11950/david-legwand-retires-after-16-nhl-seasons|title=David Legwand retires after 16 NHL seasons|website=www.nhlpa.com}}</ref> || [[Buffalo Sabres]] || Over 1,100 games played\n|-\n|[[Brad Richards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhlpa.com/news/1-12076/brad-richards-retires-from-nhl-after-15-seasons|title=BRAD RICHARDS RETIRES FROM NHL AFTER 15 SEASONS|website=www.nhlpa.com}}</ref> || [[Detroit Red Wings]] || [[Lady Byng Memorial Trophy]] winner, [[Conn Smythe Trophy]] winner, over 1,100 games played\n|-\n|[[Alex Tanguay]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/alex-tanguay-joins-nhl-network-as-studio-analyst/c-286816378|title=Alex Tanguay joins NHL Network as studio analyst|website=NHL.com}}</ref> || [[Arizona Coyotes]] || Over 1,000 games played\n|-\n|[[Dainius Zubrus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Paskelbtas ledo ritulio rinktin\u0117s kandidat\u0173 s\u0105ra\u0161as: yra ir Dainius Zubrus|url=http://sportas.lrytas.lt/startai/paskelbtas-ledo-ritulio-rinktines-kandidatu-sarasas-yra-ir-dainius-zubrus.htm|website=lrytas.lt|accessdate=12 April 2017|language=lt-LT|date=28 February 2017}}</ref> || [[San Jose Sharks]] || Over 1,200 games played\n|}\n\n===Major milestones reached===\n*On November 21, 2015, [[San Jose Sharks]] forward [[Patrick Marleau]] scored his 1,000th career point, becoming the 83rd player in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patrick Marleau gets 1,00th career point and Sharks beat Penguins 3-1|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/patrick-marleau-gets-1000th-career-point-and-sharks-beat-penguins-3-1/c-789009|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On November 27, 2015, [[Arizona Coyotes]] coach [[Dave Tippett]] won his 500th game, becoming the 22nd coach in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vest|first1=Dave|title='Yotes Notes: Players Give Tippet MVP Belt After 500th Win|url=http://coyotes.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=789991|website=Coyotes.NHL.com|publisher=Arizona Coyotes|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On December 19, 2015, [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] forward [[Phil Kessel]] played his 500th consecutive game, becoming the 23rd player in league history to reach this milestone.\n*On January 4, 2016, [[Colorado Avalanche]] forward [[Jarome Iginla]] scored his 600th NHL goal, becoming the 19th player in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sadowski|first1=Rick|title=Jarome Iginla scores 600th NHL goal, 19th to do so|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/jarome-iginla-scores-600th-nhl-goal-19th-to-do-so/c-795968|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On January 10, 2016, [[Washington Capitals]] forward [[Alexander Ovechkin]] scored his 500th NHL goal, becoming the 43rd player in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Capitals' Ovechkin scores 500th NHL goal|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/capitals-ovechkin-scores-500th-nhl-goal/c-797019|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On January 14, 2016, [[Chicago Blackhawks]] coach [[Joel Quenneville]] won his 783rd game, surpassing [[Al Arbour]] to become the second winningest coach in league history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blackhawks' Quenneville passes Arbour on wins list|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/blackhawks-quenneville-passes-arbour-on-wins-list/c-797784|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On January 21, 2016, [[Vancouver Canucks]] forward [[Daniel Sedin]] scored his 347th NHL goal, surpassing [[Markus N\u00e4slund|Markus Naslund]] for most goals in franchise history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daniel Sedin passes Markus Naslund for most goals in Canucks history|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/daniel-sedin-passes-markus-naslund-for-most-goals-in-canucks-history/|website=Sportsnet.ca|publisher=Rogers Media|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On January 26, 2016, [[San Jose Sharks]] forward [[Joe Thornton]] scored his 1,300th career point, becoming the 33rd player in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sharks' Thornton gets 1,300th NHL point|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/sharks-thornton-gets-1300th-nhl-point/c-799790|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On February 4, 2016, [[Florida Panthers]] forward [[Jarom\u00edr J\u00e1gr|Jaromir Jagr]] scored his 1,100th career assist, becoming the sixth player in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jagr becomes sixth player to reach 1,100 assists|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/jaromir-jagr-1100-assist-panthers/c-278330114?tid=277897704|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On February 13, 2016, [[Boston Bruins]] coach [[Claude Julien (ice hockey)|Claude Julien]] won his 500th game, becoming the 23rd coach in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bruins coach Julien wins 500th NHL game|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/claude-julien-wins-500th-nhl-game/c-278789576?tid=278482306|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On February 20, 2016, [[Florida Panthers]] forward [[Jarom\u00edr J\u00e1gr|Jaromir Jagr]] scored his 742nd career goal, surpassing [[Brett Hull]] to become third in career goals.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gretz|first1=Adam|title=Jaromir Jagr passes Brett Hull for 3rd on NHL all-time goal list|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/eye-on-hockey/25490222/watch-jaromir-jagr-ties-brett-hull-for-3rd-on-nhl-all-time-goal-list|website=CBSSports.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On March 7, 2016, [[Florida Panthers]] forward [[Jarom\u00edr J\u00e1gr|Jaromir Jagr]] scored his 1,851st career point, surpassing [[Gordie Howe]] to become third in career points.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Poupart|first1=Alain|title=Jagr passes Howe on points list|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/jaromir-jagr-gordie-howe-third-nhl-points-list/c-279439158?tid=279372386|website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On March 14, 2016, [[Los Angeles Kings]] goaltender [[Jonathan Quick]] recorded his 41st career shutout, surpassing both [[Frank Brimsek]] and [[John Vanbiesbrouck]] to become the all-time shutout leader for U.S.-born goaltenders.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dillman|first1=Lisa|title=Jonathan Quick makes history as Kings blank Blackhawks, 5-0|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/kings/la-sp-kings-blackhawks-20160315-story.html|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=14 March 2016|accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref>\n*On April 2, 2016, [[Dallas Stars]] coach [[Lindy Ruff]] won his 700th game, becoming the fifth coach in league history to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dallas Stars at Los Angeles Kings |url=https://www.nhl.com/gamecenter/dal-vs-lak/2016/04/02/2015021169#game=2015021169,game_state=final |website=NHL.com |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n*For the first time in the history of the NHL, Canadian-born players do not comprise a majority the league's players. Of the 680 players who appeared in games over the course of the first two weeks of the season, 49.7 percent were born in Canada, while 24.2 percent were American-born. A record 9.1 percent were from Sweden, and 4.5 percent from Russia.<ref name=\"Canadian-born not the league's majority\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/canadians-do-not-make-up-the-majority-of-nhl-players-this-season-1.380861|title=Canadians do not make up the majority of NHL players this season|last=Seravalli|first=Frank|website=TSN.ca|publisher=Bell Media|date=October 22, 2015|accessdate=October 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Uniforms==\n*The [[Anaheim Ducks]] made a minor change to their home jersey. They changed the collar laces from black to white.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nhl/story/_/id/13765035/2015-16-nhl-season-preview-uni-watch-uniform-changes-tweaks-alternates-throwbacks |title=2015-16 Uni Watch NHL preview |date=October 2, 2015 |accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref> The team also unveiled their new third jersey; the jersey shows a modern Ducks re-colouring of the old Mighty Ducks of Anaheim logo used from the 1993-94 season to the 2005\u201306 season. The jersey is primarily orange with black and bronze striping. On both shoulders it features the teams current primary logo and on one side of the collar it features the team's wordmark \"ANAHEIM\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sportslogos.net/2015/09/07/nhl-shop-leaks-ducks-avalanche-third-jerseys/|title=NHL Shop Leaks Ducks, Avalanche Third Jerseys |date=September 7, 2015 |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> \n*The [[Arizona Coyotes]] began using new home and away jerseys. The primary logo stays the same. The jerseys have added a large black stripe on each arm running from just below the shoulder to the elbow. From there it is red-white-red before it runs white right to the cuff. There's a single hem stripe, black on homes and red on the whites. The home red features a new shoulder patch, a beige/sand coyote paw print with a black \"A\" on it. The road white features a modernized \"AZ/map\" patch, with the font updated to match the new team wordmark. The pants are black, socks are red, black and white similar to the striping on each arm. The new home and away jerseys replace the home and away jerseys that the Coyotes unveiled last year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://coyotes.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=772384| title=Coyotes Reveal New Uniforms at NHL Draft Party | date=June 26, 2015 | accessdate=June 27, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Boston Bruins]] unveiled their new 2016 NHL Winter Classic uniform. The jersey is based on their jersey they wore during the 1924-25 season. The colors have been modernized as black is the primary color, gold and brown as the secondary colors. Two gold horizontal stripes are on each arm and one across the waist. The \"Boston\" wordmark arched over an illustrated bear and Bruins, the crest varies only slightly in the layout from the 1924-25 original. The crest colors celebrate both the beginning and modern day color palette of this historic franchise, and are executed in felt and chenille materials, similar to the original crest. The numbers are in your standard jersey semi-serif block lettering, names and numbers are in white or cream. The numbers on the sleeves are located between the two gold horizontal stripes. The 2016 Winter Classic logo appears on one shoulder as a patch.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bruins.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=784609| title=Bruins Unveil 2016 Bridgestone NHL Winter Classic Uniform | date=October 24, 2015 | accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Buffalo Sabres]] have scrapped their alternate jersey that was unveiled for the 2013-14 season.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sabres.buffalonews.com/2015/03/12/sabres-shelving-reviled-alternate-jersey/| title=Sabres shelving reviled alternate jersey| date=June 23, 2015| accessdate=October 2, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003174024/http://sabres.buffalonews.com/2015/03/12/sabres-shelving-reviled-alternate-jersey/| archive-date=October 3, 2015| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> In lieu of a third jersey, with special permission from the league, the team will wear their white away jerseys for six home games in this season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vogl|first=John|title=Quick hits: Sabres 4, Capitals 1|url=http://sabres.buffalonews.com/2016/01/16/quick-hits-sabres-capitals/|accessdate=January 16, 2016|work=[[The Buffalo News]]|publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|date=January 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160118195615/http://sabres.buffalonews.com/2016/01/16/quick-hits-sabres-capitals/|archive-date=2016-01-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*The [[Chicago Blackhawks]] unveiled a unique jersey for their 2016 NHL Stadium Series game. This jersey is primarily white with black/red/black stripes on the sleeves and socks. The current logo is on the chest. Framed between the two black stripes and over the red stripe on the sleeve is the  familiar \"C\" with crossed tomahawks. The collar of the jersey features two different colors. The four, six-pointed red stars from the [[Flag of Chicago]] is featured on the white portion of the collar, while the other side of the collar is black. Sleeve numbers have been shifted to the shoulders and enlarged. With the shoulders being black, the numbering is white. But, the numbering and lettering on the back is also enlarged and black in color.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sportslogos.net/2015/11/24/blackhawks-unveil-stadium-series-jersey/|title=Blackhawks, Wild Unveil Stadium Series Jerseys|work=sportslogos|accessdate=2015-11-28}}</ref>\n*The [[Colorado Avalanche]] will replace their \"Sasquatch\" alternate logo by a re-coloured \"CO\" from the State of Colorado flag.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.sportslogos.net/2015/06/26/20648/| title=Avalanche Tweak Uniform| date=June 26, 2015 | accessdate=August 4, 2015}}</ref> A new third jersey features the logo of the long-departed [[Colorado Rockies (NHL)|Colorado Rockies]], set in Avalanche colors and number font. In addition to that, they're marking their 20th anniversary with a patch on the front of their jerseys.\n*The Avalanche will also wear a special jersey, which will be primarily white with black, red and blue also featured for the 2016 NHL Stadium Series. It incorporates the same Colorado 'C' design that was added to the Avalanche jersey designs earlier this year. It also features larger numbers on the back and on the shoulders. The collar features a \"5280\" call out, referencing the Avalanche's home in the Mile-High City.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://avalanche.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=779906| title=Avs reveal Coors Light NHL Stadium Series sweater | date=September 21, 2015 | accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Columbus Blue Jackets]] altered their home and road jerseys slightly. The blue Union Army cap shoulder patch worn from the 2003\u201304 season until the 2014\u201315 season was replaced with a new shoulder patch logo. The new shoulder patch logo features the [[Field artillery in the American Civil War#12-pounder Napoleon|1857 Napoleon]] [[cannon]]. It is very similar to the club's current third jersey logo, with the only difference is that the logo features the club's primary colors \u2013 Navy Blue, Red, Silver and White.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bluejackets.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=772327| title=Blue Jackets unveil new secondary mark to be worn as shoulder patch | date=June 26, 2015 | accessdate=June 27, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Detroit Red Wings]] unveiled a unique jersey for their 2016 NHL Stadium Series game. This jersey is primarily red with a diagonal white stripe across the chest. Featured inside the diagonal white stripe is the large red redesigned \"D\" logo. The current Red Wings logo is featured on one shoulder and the 2016 Stadium Series logo is featured on the other shoulder. The word \"EST 1926\" is written on the inside rear collar and the word \"RED WINGS\" is written on one side of the front collar. The jersey also features large numbers on the back and on the shoulder as well as a nameplate featuring arched lettering which is all white in color.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://redwings.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=789249| title=Red Wings unveil Stadium Series jersey | date=November 23, 2015 | accessdate=November 29, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Edmonton Oilers]] unveiled a new alternate jersey. This new throwback jersey is a remake of the jersey worn by the franchise during their inaugural season as the Alberta Oilers of the [[World Hockey Association]]. The jersey is orange with blue and white shoulders and blue/white/blue stripes on the sleeves. The numbers are in the same location as the original WHA jersey on which they are based.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://oilers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=772311| title=Edmonton Oilers Unveil Orange Jersey | date=June 26, 2015 | accessdate=June 28, 2015}}</ref>  \n*The [[Minnesota Wild]] unveiled a unique jersey for their 2016 NHL Stadium Series game. This jersey is primarily green with red and beige stripes on the sleeves. Beige is also featured on the shoulders. The current logo is on the chest. On the left shoulder is their \"State of Hockey\" logo and on the right shoulder is the 2016 Stadium Series logo. The numbering and lettering which are beige in color are enlarged on the sleeve and on the back of the jersey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sportslogos.net/2015/11/24/blackhawks-unveil-stadium-series-jersey/ |title=Blackhawks, Wild Unveil Stadium Series Jerseys |date=November 24, 2015 |accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref> \n*The [[Montreal Canadiens]] made some slight alterations to their home and away jerseys. Four brass hexagonal eyelets and white laces will be reintroduced around the collar, which will also revert to pure white in color. On the team's red home jersey, the French \"LNH\" logo will be stitched at the nape of the neck, and the lone exception to the English \"NHL\" on the away jersey. It is very similar to the club's home and away jerseys worn from the 1970\u201371 season to the 1974\u201375 season. The new home and away jerseys replace the home and away jerseys worn from the 2007\u201308 season until the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://canadiens.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=771966&navid=DL%7CMTL%7Chome |title=Montreal Canadiens unveil new 2015\u201316 jersey |date=June 26, 2015 |accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Montreal Canadiens]] unveiled their 2016 NHL Winter Classic jerseys. The chest stripe is a shade of blue. The \"C\" is white and the \"H\" is red, as they were in 1923-24. An image of the globe is on the sleeves that closely resembles the 1925 version. The French \"LNH\" logo will be stitched near the collar. Other features included into the design are a red collar, red letters, red numbers and red stripes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://canadiens.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=786640 |title=Montreal Canadiens unveil jersey for 2016 Bridgestone NHL Winter Classic |date=November 6, 2015 |accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref> \n*The [[Nashville Predators]] added the 2016 NHL All-Star Game logo as their patch on the front of their jerseys.  They hosted it on January 31, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lukas|first=Paul|title=2015-16 Uni Watch NHL preview|url=http://espn.go.com/nhl/story/_/id/13765035/2015-16-nhl-season-preview-uni-watch-uniform-changes-tweaks-alternates-throwbacks|website=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=October 2, 2015|date=October 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[Nashville Predators]] normally wear blue helmets with their gold home jerseys, but this season they'll switch to gold helmets for Saturday home games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://predators.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=776717 |title=Nashville Predators Launch \"Golden Saturdays\" During 2015-16 Season |date=June 26, 2015 |accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[New York Islanders]] unveiled a new alternate jersey. This New Jersey is in black with white trim, with blue and orange relegated to the back collar. The \"NY\" wordmark from the Stadium Series thirds was moved to the new alternates, sans the chrome accents. The new third jersey replaces the Stadium Series third jerseys the Islanders wore in the 2014\u201315 season.<ref name=\"Islanders Unveil New Third Jersey\">{{cite web |url=http://islanders.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=779255 |title=Islanders Unveil New Third Jersey|date=September 16, 2015 |accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[New York Islanders]] added a patch on the right shoulder of the jerseys commemorating their first season in Brooklyn.<ref name=\"Islanders Unveil New Third Jersey\"/> In addition to that, they have also added a left shoulder \"Al\" patch in memory of former coach [[Al Arbour]] who died on August 28, 2015, at the age of 82.<ref name=\"Islanders Unveil New Third Jersey\"/>\n*The [[San Jose Sharks]]  added a 25th anniversary patch. The patch features a new, \"swimming\" Shark with an exposed tail hovering above a diamond-encrusted \"25\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Sharks unveil new logos, commemorative patches for 25th anniversary season|url=http://blogs.mercurynews.com/sharks/2015/06/29/sharks-unveil-new-logos-commemorative-patches-for-25th-anniversary-season/?doing_wp_cron=1435599481.1435539722442626953125|accessdate=June 29, 2015|work=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|publisher=[[Digital First Media]]|date=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n*The [[San Jose Sharks]] unveiled their \"heritage jersey.\" This design is identical to the road jerseys worn from 1991-92 season through 1997-98 season, adapted to the [[Reebok Edge]] uniform system.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sharks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=778847| title= Sharks Unveil Heritage Jersey | date=September 12, 2015 | accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref> \n*The [[Washington Capitals]] added a new alternate jersey to their lineup. The primary color for the uniform is red and closely resembles the team's jersey worn from 1974\u201375 season through 1994\u201395 season. The original Capitals wordmark is featured on the front of the jersey with six stars above it and five stars beneath the numbers on each sleeve. The Capitals will wear blue pants and red helmets with their third jerseys. The new third jersey replaces the white third jersey the Capitals wore from the 2011\u201312 season to the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://capitalstoday.monumentalnetwork.com/2015/06/23/capitals-unveil-new-third-jersey-for-2015-16| title=Capitals unveil new third jersey for 2015\u201316 | date=June 23, 2015 | accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2015\u201316 NHL transactions]]\n*[[2015\u201316 NHL suspensions and fines]]\n*[[List of 2015\u201316 NHL Three Star Awards|2015\u201316 NHL Three Star Awards]]\n*[[2016 Stanley Cup playoffs|2016 NHL playoffs]]\n*[[2015 in sports]]\n*[[2016 in sports]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nhl.com/ice/schedulebyseason.htm?season=20152016&gameType=2&team=&network=&venue= 2015\u201316 NHL season Schedule]\n\n{{NHL seasons|2015}}\n{{2015\u201316 NHL season by team}}\n{{2015\u201316 in men's ice hockey}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2015-16 Nhl season}}\n[[Category:2015\u201316 NHL season| ]]\n[[Category:2015\u201316 in American ice hockey by league|1]]\n[[Category:2015\u201316 in Canadian ice hockey by league|1]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: teams current primary \u2192 team's current primary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015%E2%80%9316_NHL_season"}
{"title_page": "Proto-Altaic language", "text_new": "{{Infobox proto-language\n| name             = Proto-Altaic\n| familycolor      = Altaic\n| acceptance = disputed\n| target             = [[Altaic languages]]\n| child1 = [[Proto-Mongolic]]\n| child2 = [[Proto-Turkic]]\n| child3 = [[Proto-Japonic]]\n}}\nThe '''Proto-Altaic language''' is a hypothetical extinct language that has been proposed as the [[Protolanguage|common ancestor]] of the [[Altaic languages]].\n\nIn the 18th century, some similarities between the [[Turkic languages|Turkic]], [[Mongolian languages|Mongolian]], and [[Tungusic languages]] led to the conjecture that they would be a single [[language family]] with a common ancestral language.<ref name=poppe65>Nicholas Poppe (1965): ''Introduction to Altaic Linguistics.'' Volume 14 of ''Ural-altaische Bibliothek''. Otto Harrassowitz, Wiesbaden.</ref>{{rp|page 125}}  Starting in the 19th century, some linguists proposed to include also the [[Japonic languages|Japonic]] and/or [[Koreanic languages]] as well as the [[Ainu language]], forming what would later be called the \"Macro-Altaic family\" (the original one being then dubbed \"Micro-Altaic\").<ref name=miller86>Roy Andrew Miller (1986): ''Nihongo: In Defence of Japanese.'' {{ISBN|0-485-11251-5}}.</ref>{{rp|34}} Around the same time others proposed to include the [[Finno-Ugric languages|Finno-Ugric]] and [[Samoyedic languages]] in a [[Ural-Altaic languages|Ural-Altaic family]].<ref name=poppe65/>{{rp|126\u2013127}}\n\nVersions of the Altaic family hypothesis were widely accepted until the 1960s, and is still listed in many encyclopedias and handbooks.<ref name=georg1999>Stefan Georg, Peter A. Michalove, Alexis Manaster Ramer, and Paul J. Sidwell (1999): \"[http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract;jsessionid=A7D36A55C4A29AEB34AA39715F46F706.tomcat1?fromPage=online&aid=17033 Telling general linguists about Altaic]\". ''Journal of Linguistics'', volume 35, issue 1, pages 65\u201398.</ref>{{rp|73}}  However, in recent decades the proposal has received substantial criticisms, and has been rejected by many [[comparative method|comparative linguists]].<ref>Lyle Campbell and Mauricio J. Mixco (2007): ''A Glossary of Historical Linguistics'', page 7 University of Utah Press.</ref><ref>Johanna Nichols (1992) ''Linguistic Diversity in Space and Time'', page 4. Chicago University Press.</ref><ref>R. M. W. Dixon (1997): ''The Rise and Fall of Languages'', page 32.  Cambridge University Press.</ref>\n\nNevertheless, \"Altaicists\" (supporters of the theory of a common origin for the Altaic languages) such as [[V\u00e1clav Bla\u017eek]] and [[Sergei Starostin]] have endeavored to reconstruct \"Proto-Altaic\", the hypothetical common ancestral language of the family.\n\nSome Altaicists have proposed that the [[urheimat|original area]] where Proto-(Macro-)Altaic would have been spoken was a relatively small area comprising present-day North Korea, Southern Manchuria, and Southeastern Mongolia.<ref name=johrob2010>Lars Johanson and Martine Irma Robbeets (2010): ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=9zcxQqmkgE0C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Transeurasian Verbal Morphology in a Comparative Perspective: Genealogy, Contact, Chance.]''. Introduction to the book,  pages 1-5.</ref>  The date for its split into the major recognized families was estimated at 5000 BC<ref name=staro2003/> or 6000 BC.<ref>Elena E. Kuz'mina (2007): ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=x5J9rn8p2-IC&pg=PP1&redir_esc=y# The Origin of the Indo-Iranians]'', page 364. Brill. {{ISBN|978-9004160-54-5}}</ref> This would make Altaic a language family about as old as [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] (4000 to 7,000 BC according to several hypotheses<ref>Mallory (1997): Page 106</ref>) but considerably younger than [[Afroasiatic languages|Afroasiatic]] (c. 10,000 BC<ref>Igor M. Diakonoff (1988): ''Afrasian Languages.'' Nauka, Moscow.</ref>{{rp|33}} or 11,000 to 16,000 BC<ref>Ehret (2002)<!--Bibliographic data needed--></ref>{{rp|35\u201336}} according to different sources).\n\n==Reconstruction==\n{{As of|2019}}, the most comprehensive attempt at reconstructing a Proto-(Macro)-Altaic language is the 2003 ''Etymological Dictionary of the Altaic Languages'' by Starostin, [[Anna Dybo|Dybo]] and [[Oleg Mudrak|Mudrak]],<ref name=staro2003>Sergei Starostin, Anna V. Dybo, and Oleg A. Mudrak (2003): ''Etymological Dictionary of the Altaic Languages'', 3 volumes. {{ISBN|90-04-13153-1}}.</ref> which was summarized in 2006 by Bla\u017eek.<ref name=blazek2006>V\u00e1clav Bla\u017eek (2006): \"[http://www.phil.muni.cz/linguistica/art/blazek/bla-004.pdf Current progress in Altaic etymology.]\" ''Linguistica Online'', 30 January 2006. Accessed on 2019-03-22.</ref>\n\n===Reconstructed phonology===\nBased on the proposed correspondences listed below, the following [[phoneme]] inventory (in [[help:IPA|IPA]] notation) has been reconstructed for the hypothetical Proto(-Macro)-Altaic language.\n\n====Consonants====\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n! [[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar or dental]]\n! [[Alveolo-palatal consonant|Alveolopalatal]]\n! [[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]]\n!&nbsp;[[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]&nbsp;\n!&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Velar consonant|Velar]]&nbsp;&nbsp;\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"3\" | [[Plosives]]\n! <small>[[Aspirated consonant|aspirated]]</small>\n| /p\u02b0/\n| /t\u02b0/\n|\n|\n|\n| /k\u02b0/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! <small>[[Voicelessness|voiceless]]</small>\n| /p/\n| /t/\n|\n|\n|\n| /k/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! <small>[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small>\n| /b/\n| /d/\n|\n|\n|\n| /\u0261/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"3\" | [[Affricate consonant|Affricates]]\n! <small>[[Aspirated consonant|aspirated]]</small>\n|\n|\n|\n| /t\u0283\u02b0/\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! <small>[[Voicelessness|voiceless]]</small>\n|\n|\n|\n| /t\u0283/\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! <small>[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small>\n|\n|\n|\n| /d\u0292/\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Fricative consonant|Fricatives]]\n! <small>[[Voicelessness|voiceless]]</small>\n|\n| /s/\n|\n| /\u0283/\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! <small>[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small>\n|\n| /z/-<sup>1</sup>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Nasal stop|Nasals]]\n| /m/\n| /n/\n| /n\u02b2/\n|\n|\n| /\u014b/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Trill consonant|Trills]]\n|\n| -/r/-<sup>2</sup>\n| /r\u02b2/\n|\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Approximant consonant|Approximants]]\n|\n| /l/\n| /l\u02b2/\n|\n| -/j/-<sup>2</sup>\n|\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> This phoneme only occurred at the beginnings of words.<br>\n<sup>2</sup> These phonemes only occurred in the interior of words.\n\n====Vowels====\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Front vowel|Front]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Back vowel|Back]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center; font-size: x-small;\"\n! [[Roundedness|unrounded]]\n! [[Roundedness|rounded]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| /i/\n| /y/\n| /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n| /e/\n| /\u00f8/\n| /o/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Near-open vowel|Near-open]]\n| /\u00e6/\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Open vowel|Open]]\n| colspan=\"3\" | /a/\n|}\n\nIt is not clear whether {{IPA|/\u00e6/}}, {{IPA|/\u00f8/}}, {{IPA|/y/}} were [[monophthong]]s as shown here (presumably {{IPA|[\u00e6 \u0153~\u00f8 \u028f~y]}}) or [[diphthong]]s ({{IPA|[i\u032fa~i\u032f\u0251 i\u032f\u0254~i\u032fo i\u032f\u028a~i\u032fu]}}); the evidence is equivocal. In any case, however, they only occurred in the first (and sometimes only) syllable of any word.\n\nEvery vowel occurred in long and short versions which were different [[phoneme]]s in the first syllable. Starostin et al. (2003) treat length together with pitch as a prosodic feature.\n\n====Prosody====\nAs reconstructed by Starostin et al. (2003), Proto-Altaic was a [[pitch accent]] or [[Tone (linguistics)|tone]] language; at least the first and probably every syllable could have a high or a low pitch.\n\n===Sound correspondences===\nIf a Proto(-Macro)-Altaic language really existed, it should be possible to reconstruct regular sound correspondences between that [[protolanguage]] and its descendants; such correspondences would make it possible to distinguish [[cognate]]s from [[loanword]]s (in many cases). Such attempts have repeatedly been made. The latest version is reproduced here, taken from Bla\u017eek's (2006) summary of the newest Altaic etymological dictionary (Starostin et al. 2003) and transcribed into the [[help:IPA|IPA]].\n\nWhen a Proto-Altaic phoneme developed differently depending on its position in a word (beginning, interior, or end), the special case (or all cases) is marked with a hyphen; for example, Proto-Altaic {{IPA|/p\u02b0/}} disappears (marked \"0\") or becomes {{IPA|/j/}} at the beginning of a Turkic word and becomes {{IPA|/p/}} elsewhere in a Turkic word.\n\n====Consonants====\nOnly single consonants are considered here. In the middle of words, clusters of two consonants were allowed in Proto-Altaic as reconstructed by Starostin et al. (2003); the correspondence table of these clusters spans almost seven pages in their book (83\u201389), and most clusters are only found in one or a few of the reconstructed roots.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Proto-Altaic\n! Proto-Turkic\n! Proto-Mongolic\n! Proto-Tungusic\n! Proto-Korean\n! Proto-Japonic\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /p\u02b0/\n| 0-<sup>1</sup>, /j/-, /p/\n| /h/-<sup>2</sup>, /j/-, -/b/-, -/h/-<sup>2</sup>, -/b/\n| /p/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /p/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /p/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /p/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /b/\n| /b/-<sup>6</sup>, /h/-<sup>2</sup>, /b/\n| /p/-, /b/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /b/\n| /b/-, -/h/-, -/b/-<sup>9</sup>, -/b/\n| /b/\n| /p/, -/b/-\n| /p/-, /w/, /b/<sup>10</sup>, /p/<sup>11</sup>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /t\u02b0/\n| /t/-, /d/-<sup>3</sup>, /t/\n| /t/, /t\u0283/<sup>4</sup>, -/d/\n| /t/\n| /t/\n| /t/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /t/\n| /d/-, /t/\n| /t/, /t\u0283/<sup>4</sup>\n| /d/-, /d\u0292/-<sup>7</sup>, /t/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /t/, -/r/-\n| /t/-, /d/-, /t/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /d/\n| /j/-, /d/\n| /d/, /d\u0292/<sup>4</sup>\n| /d/\n| /d/-, /t/-, /t/, /j/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /t\u0283\u02b0/\n| /t\u0283/\n| /t\u0283/\n| /t\u0283/\n|rowspan=\"3\"| /t\u0283/\n| /t/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /t\u0283/\n| /d/-, /t\u0283/\n| /d/-, /d\u0292/-<sup>4</sup>, /t\u0283/\n| /s/-, -/d\u0292/-, -/s/-\n| /t/-, -/s/-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /d\u0292/\n| /j/\n| /d\u0292/\n| /d\u0292/\n| /d/-, /j/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /k\u02b0/\n| /k/\n| /k/-, -/k/-, -/\u0261/-<sup>5</sup>, -/\u0261/\n| /x/-, /k/, /x/\n| /k/, /h/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /k/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /k/\n| /k/-, /k/, /\u0261/<sup>8</sup>\n| /k/-, /\u0261/\n| /k/-, /\u0261/-, /\u0261/\n| /k/-, -/h/-, -0-, -/k/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /\u0261/\n| /\u0261/\n| /\u0261/-, -/h/-, -/\u0261/-<sup>5</sup>, -/\u0261/\n| /\u0261/\n| /k/, -/h/-, -0-\n| /k/-, /k/, 0<sup>12</sup>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /s/\n| /s/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /s/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /s/\n| /s/-, /h/-, /s/\n|rowspan=\"3\"| /s/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /z/\n| /j/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /s/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /\u0283/\n| /s/-, /t\u0283/-<sup>13</sup>, /s/\n| /s/-, /t\u0283/-<sup>13</sup>, /s/\n| /\u0283/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /m/\n| /b/-, -/m/-\n| /m/\n| /m/\n| /m/\n| /m/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /n/\n| /j/-, -/n/-\n| /n/\n| /n/\n| /n/\n| /n/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /n\u02b2/\n| /j/-, /n\u02b2/\n| /d\u0292/-, /j/, /n/\n| /n\u02b2/\n| /n/-, /n\u02b2/<sup>14</sup>\n| /m/-, /n/, /m/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /\u014b/\n| 0-, /j/-, /\u014b/\n| 0-, /j/-, /\u0261/-<sup>15</sup>, /n/-<sup>16</sup>, /\u014b/, /n/, /m/, /h/\n| /\u014b/\n| /n/-, /\u014b/, 0\n| 0-, /n/-, /m/-<sup>7</sup>, /m/, /n/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /r/\n| /r/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /r/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /r/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /r/\n| /r/, /t/<sup>4, 15</sup>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /r\u02b2/\n| /r\u02b2/\n| /r/, /t/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /l/\n| /j/-, /l/\n| /n/-, /l/-, /l/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /l/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /n/-, /r/\n| /n/-, /r/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /l\u02b2/\n| /j/-, /l\u02b2/\n| /d/-, /d\u0292/-<sup>4</sup>, /l/\n| /n/-, /s/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /j/\n| /j/\n| /j/, /h/\n| /j/\n| /j/, 0\n| /j/, 0\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> The [[Turkic Khalaj language|Khalaj language]] has {{IPA|/h/}} instead. (It also retains a number of other archaisms.) However, it has also added {{IPA|/h/}} in front of words for which no initial consonant (except in some cases {{IPA|/\u014b/}}, as expected) can be reconstructed for Proto-Altaic; therefore, and because it would make them dependent on whether Khalaj happens to have preserved any given root, Starostin et al. (2003: 26\u201328) have not used Khalaj to decide whether to reconstruct an initial {{IPA|/p\u02b0/}} in any given word and have not reconstructed a {{IPA|/h/}} for Proto-Turkic even though it was probably there.<br>\n<sup>2</sup> The [[Monguor language]] has {{IPA|/f/}} here instead (Kaiser & Shevoroshkin 1988); it is therefore possible that Proto-Mongolian also had {{IPA|/f/}} which then became {{IPA|/h/}} (and then usually disappeared) in all descendants except Monguor. Tabga\u010d and [[Khitan language|Kitan]], two extinct Mongolic languages not considered by Starostin et al. (2003), even preserve {{IPA|/p/}} in these places (Bla\u017eek 2006).<br>\n<sup>3</sup> This happened when the next consonant in the word was {{IPA|/l\u02b2/}}, {{IPA|/r\u02b2/}}, or {{IPA|/r/}}.<br>\n<sup>4</sup> Before {{IPA|/i/}}.<br>\n<sup>5</sup> When the next consonant in the word was {{IPA|/h/}}.<br>\n<sup>6</sup> This happened \"in syllables with original high pitch\" (Starostin et al. 2003:135).<br>\n<sup>7</sup> Before {{IPA|/\u00e6/}}, {{IPA|/\u00f8/}} or {{IPA|/y/}}.<br>\n<sup>8</sup> When the next consonant in the word was {{IPA|/r/}}.<br>\n<sup>9</sup> When the preceding consonant was {{IPA|/r/}}, {{IPA|/r\u02b2/}}, {{IPA|/l/}}, or {{IPA|/l\u02b2/}}, or when the next consonant was {{IPA|/\u0261/}}.<br>\n<sup>10</sup> Before {{IPA|/a/}}, {{IPA|/\u0259/}}, or any vowel followed by {{IPA|/j/}}.<br>\n<sup>11</sup> Before {{IPA|/j/}}, or {{IPA|/i/}} and then another vowel.<br>\n<sup>12</sup> When preceded by a vowel preceded by {{IPA|/i/}}.<br>\n<sup>13</sup> Before {{IPA|/a/}}.<br>\n<sup>14</sup> Starostin et al. (2003) follow a minority opinion (Vovin 1993) in interpreting the sound of the Middle Korean letter \u1140 as {{IPA|[n\u02b2]}} or {{IPA|[\u0272]}} rather than {{IPA|[z]}}. (Dybo & Starostin 2008:footnote 50)<br>\n<sup>15</sup> Before {{IPA|/u/}}.<br>\n<sup>16</sup> Before {{IPA|/a/}}, {{IPA| /o/}}, or {{IPA|/e/}}.\n\n====Vowels====\n[[Vowel harmony]] is pervasive in the languages attributed to Altaic: most Turkic and Mongolic as well as some Tungusic languages have it, Korean is arguably in the process of losing its traces, and it is controversially hypothesized for Old Japanese. (Vowel harmony is also typical of the neighboring [[Uralic languages]] and was often counted among the arguments for the [[Ural\u2013Altaic languages|Ural\u2013Altaic hypotheses]].) Nevertheless, Starostin et al. (2003) reconstruct Proto-Altaic as lacking vowel harmony. Instead, according to them, vowel harmony originated in each daughter branch as assimilation of the vowel in the first syllable to the vowel in the second syllable (which was usually modified or lost later). \"The situation therefore is very close, e.g. to [[Germanic languages|Germanic]] [see [[Germanic umlaut]]] or to the [[Nakh languages]] in the Eastern Caucasus, where the quality of non-initial vowels can now only be recovered on the basis of umlaut processes in the first syllable.\" (Starostin et al. 2003:91) The table below is taken from Starostin et al. (2003):\n\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | Proto-Altaic\n! Proto-Turkic\n! Proto-Mongolic\n! Proto-Tungusic\n! Middle Korean\n! Proto-Japonic\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! first s.\n! second s.\n! colspan=\"5\" | first syllable\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!rowspan=\"5\"| /a/\n! /a/\n| /a/, /a/<sup>1</sup>, /\u028c/<sup>1</sup>\n| /a/\n|rowspan=\"5\"| /a/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /a/, /e/\n| /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /e/\n| /a/, /\u026f/\n| /a/, /i/\n| /\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /i/\n| /\u025b/, /a/\n| /a/, /e/\n| /a/, /e/, /i/\n| /i/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /o/\n| /o/, /ja/, /aj/\n| /a/, /i/, /e/\n| /\u0259/, /o/\n| /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /u/\n| /a/\n| /a/, /o/, /u/\n| /a/, /\u0259/, /o/, /u/\n| /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!rowspan=\"5\"| /e/\n! /a/\n| /a/, /\u028c/, /\u025b/\n| /a/, /e/\n|rowspan=\"5\"| /e/\n| /a/, /e/\n| /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /e/\n| /ja/-, /\u025b/, /e/<sup>2</sup>\n| /e/, /ja/\n| /a/, /e/, /i/, /\u0268/\n| /\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /i/\n| /ja/-, /\u025b/, /e/<sup>2</sup>\n| /e/, /i/\n| /i/, /\u0268/, /a/, /e/\n| /i/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /o/\n| /\u028c/, /e/\n| /a/, /e/, /y/<sup>3</sup>, /\u00f8/<sup>3</sup>\n| /\u0259/, /o/, /u/\n| /\u0259/, /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /u/\n| /\u025b/, /a/, /\u028c/\n| /e/, /a/, /o/<sup>3</sup>\n| /o/, /u/, /a/\n| /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!rowspan=\"5\"| /i/\n! /a/\n| /\u026f/, /i/\n| /i/\n|rowspan=\"5\"| /i/\n| /a/, /e/\n| /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /e/\n| {{IPA|/\u025b/}}, /e/<sup>2</sup>\n| /e/, /i/\n| /i/, /\u0268/\n| /i/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /i/\n| /i/\n| /i/, /e/<sup>1</sup>\n| /i/\n| /i/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /o/\n| /\u026f/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /i/\n| /o/, /u/, /\u0268/\n| /i/, /\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /u/\n| /\u026f/, /i/\n| /i/, /\u0268/\n| /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!rowspan=\"5\"| /o/\n! /a/\n| /o/\n| /o/, /u/\n|rowspan=\"5\"| /o/, /u/\n| /a/, /e/\n| /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /e/\n| /\u00f8/, /o/\n| /\u00f8/, /y/, /o/\n| /\u0268/, /o/, /u/\n| /\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /i/\n| /\u00f8/, /o/\n| /\u00f8/\n| /o/, /u/\n| /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /o/\n| /o/\n| /u/\n| /a/, /e/\n| /\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /u/\n| /o/\n| /o/, /u/\n| /\u0259/, /o/, /u/\n| /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!rowspan=\"5\"| /u/\n! /a/\n| /u/, /o/\n| /a/, /o/, /u/\n| /o/, /u/\n| /a/, /e/\n| /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /e/\n| /y/\n| /o/, /u/, /y/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /u/\n| /a/, /e/\n| /ua/, /a/<sup>1</sup>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /i/\n| /y/, /u/\n| /y/, /\u00f8/\n| /o/, /u/, /\u0268/\n| /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /o/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /u/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /o/, /u/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /o/, /u/\n| /o/, /u/, /\u0268/\n| /\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /u/\n| /o/, /u/\n| /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!rowspan=\"5\"| /\u00e6/\n! /a/\n| /ia/, /ja/, /\u025b/\n| /a/\n| /ia/, /i/<sup>4</sup>\n| /\u0259/, /a/<sup>3</sup>\n| /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /e/\n| /ia/, /ja/\n| /i/, /a/, /e/\n| /i/\n| /i/, /e/, /je/\n| /\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /i/\n| /ia/, /ja/, /\u025b/\n| /i/, /e/\n| /ia/, /i/<sup>4</sup>\n| /\u0259/, /e/, /je/\n| /i/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /o/\n| /ia/, /ja/, /a/<sup>1</sup>\n| /e/\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /o/, /u/\n| /\u0259/, /o/, /u/\n| /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /u/\n| /e/, /a/, /\u028c/<sup>1</sup>\n| /a/, /o/, /u/\n| /o/, /u/, /e/, /je/\n| /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!rowspan=\"5\"| /\u00f8/\n! /a/\n| /ia/, /ja/, /a/<sup>1</sup>\n| /a/, /o/, /u/\n|rowspan=\"3\"| /o/, /u/\n| /o/, /u/, /\u0259/\n| /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /e/\n| /e/, /a/, /\u028c/<sup>1</sup>\n| /e/, /\u00f8/\n| /o/, /u/, /je/\n| /\u0259/, /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /i/\n| /ia/, /ja/, /a/<sup>1</sup>\n| /i/, /e/, /\u00f8/\n| /o/, /u/, /\u0259/\n| /i/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /o/\n| /o/, /u/\n| /\u00f8/, /y/, /o/, /u/\n| /i/\n| /i/, /e/, /je/\n| /\u0259/, /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /u/\n| /u/, /o/\n| /e/, /i/, /u/\n| /ia/, /i/<sup>4</sup>\n| /\u0259/, /u/, /je/\n| /u/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!rowspan=\"5\"| /y/\n! /a/\n| /\u026f/\n| /o/, /u/, /i/\n| /o/, /u/\n| /a/, /e/\n| /a/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /e/\n| /y/, /\u00f8/, /i/<sup>2</sup>\n|rowspan=\"2\"| /\u00f8/, /y/, /o/, /u/\n| /y/, /u/<sup>1</sup>\n| /a/, /e/, /ja/, /je/, /o/, /u/\n| /u/, /\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /i/\n| /y/, /\u00f8/\n| /i/, /u/<sup>1</sup>\n| /\u0268/, /i/, /o/, /u/\n| /i/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /o/\n| /u/, /o/\n| /o/, /u/\n| /y/\n| /a/, /e/, /ja/, /je/, /o/, /u/\n| /u/, /\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! /u/\n| /\u026f/\n| /i/, /o/, /u/, /y/, /\u00f8/\n| /o/, /u/\n| /o/, /u/, /i/, /\u0268/\n| /u/\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> When preceded by a bilabial consonant.<br>\n<sup>2</sup> When followed by a trill, {{IPA|/l/}}, or {{IPA|/l\u02b2/}}.<br>\n<sup>3</sup> When preceded or followed by a bilabial consonant.<br>\n<sup>4</sup> When preceded by a fricative ({{IPA|/s/, /\u0283/, /x/}}).\n\n====Prosody====\nLength and pitch in the first syllable evolved as follows according to Starostin et al. (2003), with the caveat that it is not clear which pitch was high and which was low in Proto-Altaic (Starostin et al. 2003:135). For simplicity of input and display every syllable is symbolized as \"a\" here:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Proto-Altaic\n! Proto-Turkic\n! Proto-Mongolic\n! Proto-Tungusic\n! Proto-Korean\n! Proto-Japonic\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! {{IPA|\u00e1}}\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|a}}<sup>1</sup>\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|\u00e0}}<sup>2</sup>\n| {{IPA|\u00e1}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! {{IPA|\u00e0}}\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|\u00e1}}\n| {{IPA|\u00e0}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! {{IPA|\u00e1\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|a\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|a}}<sup>1</sup>\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|\u00e0}}<sup>2</sup>\n| {{IPA|\u00e1}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! {{IPA|\u00e0\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|a\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u00e1}}\n| {{IPA|\u00e0}}\n|}\n\n\u00b9 \"Proto-Mongolian has lost all traces of the original prosody except for voicing *p > *b in syllables with original high pitch\" (Starostin et al. 2003:135).<br>\n\u00b2 \"[...] several secondary metatonic processes happened [...] in Korean, basically in the verb subsystem: all verbs have a strong tendency towards low pitch on the first syllable.\" (Starostin et al. 2003:135)\n\n===Morphological correspondences===\nStarostin et al. (2003) have reconstructed the following correspondences between the case and number [[suffix]]es (or [[clitic]]s) of the (Macro-)Altaic languages (taken from Bla\u017eek, 2006):\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"6\" | Case\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Proto-Altaic\n! Proto-Turkic (*), Old Turkic\n! Proto-Mongolic (*), Classical Mongolian\n! Proto-Tungusic\n! Proto-Korean (*), Middle Korean\n! Proto-Japonic (*), Old Japanese\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Nominative case|nominative]]: -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Accusative case|accusative]]: {{IPA|/be/}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/ba/, /be/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|/wo/}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Partitive case|partitive]]: {{IPA|/\u0261a/}}\n| {{IPA|-/\u0281/, -/\u026f\u0281/, -/\u0261/, -/i\u0261/}}\n| {{IPA|*-/\u0281/}} (accusative)\n| {{IPA|/\u0261a/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|/\u0261a/}} (possessive)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Genitive case|genitive]]: {{IPA|-/n\u02b2V/}}\n| {{IPA|-/\u014b/}}\n| {{IPA|*-/n/}}\n| {{IPA|-/\u014bi/}}\n| {{IPA|-/n\u02b2/}}\n| {{IPA|/no/}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Dative case|dative]]-[[Locative case|locative]]: {{IPA|/du/, /da/}}\n| {{IPA|-/ta/, -/da/, -/te/, -/de/}} (locative-ablative)\n| {{IPA|-/da/}} (dative-locative), {{IPA|-/du/}} ([[Attributive case|attributive]])\n| {{IPA|/du/}} (dative), {{IPA|-/da\u02d0/}} (locative)\n|\n| {{IPA|-/tu/}} (attributive-locative)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! dative-[[Instrumental case|instrumental]]: {{IPA|-/nV/}}\n| {{IPA|-/n/, -/\u026fn/, -/in/}} (instrumental)\n|\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/ni/}} (dative-locative)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! dative-[[Directive case|directive]]: {{IPA|-/k\u02b0V/}}\n| {{IPA|-/qa/, -/ke/}} (dative)\n|\n| {{IPA|/ki\u02d0/}} (directive)\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Comitative case|comitative]]-locative: {{IPA|-/lV/}}\n| {{IPA|-/li/, -/l\u026f\u0281/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|/la\u02d0/}} (locative), {{IPA|-/li\u02d0/}} ([[Prolative case|prolative]]), {{IPA|-/lu\u0281a/}} (comitative)\n| {{IPA|-/ro/}} (instrumental-[[Lative case|lative]])\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! comitative-[[Equative case|equative]]: {{IPA|-/t\u0283\u02b0a/}}\n| {{IPA|-/\u010d{{okina}}a/}} (equative)\n| {{IPA|/t\u0283a/}} (ablative), {{IPA|/t\u0283a/, /t\u0283a\u0281a/}} (terminative)\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|-/to/}} (comitative)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Allative case|allative]]: {{IPA|-/\u0261V/}}\n| {{IPA|-/\u0281aru/, -/\u0261ery/}} (directive)\n| {{IPA|*-/\u0281a/, -/a/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0261i\u02d0/}} (allative)\n| {{IPA|-/ei/}}\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! directive: {{IPA|-/rV/}}\n| {{IPA|-/\u0281aru/, -/\u0261ery/}}\n| {{IPA|-/ru/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|-/ro/}} (lative)\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! instrumental-ablative: {{IPA|-/d\u0292V/}}\n| *?{{IPA|-/i/}} terminal dative\n|\n| {{IPA|/d\u0292i/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|/ju/}} (ablative)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Singulative case|singulative]]: {{IPA|-/nV/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|*-/n/}}\n| {{IPA|-/n/}}\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"6\" | Number\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[dual (grammatical number)|dual]]: {{IPA|-/r\u02b2V/}}\n| {{IPA|*-/r\u02b2/}} (plural for paired objects)\n|\n| {{IPA|-/r/}} (plural)\n|\n| {{IPA|*-/r\u0259/}} (plural for paired objects)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! plural: {{IPA|-/t\u02b0/-}}\n| {{IPA|*-/t/}}\n| {{IPA|-/d/}}\n| {{IPA|-/ta/, -/te/, -/tan/, -/ten/}}\n| {{IPA|*-/t\u0268r/}}\n| {{IPA|*-/tati/}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! plural: {{IPA|-/s/-}}\n|\n| {{IPA|*-/s/}}\n| {{IPA|-/sal/}}\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! plural: {{IPA|-/l/-}}\n| {{IPA|*-/lar/}}\n| {{IPA|*-/nar/}}\n| {{IPA|-/l/, -/sal/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|*-/ra/}}\n|}\n\n/V/ symbolizes an uncertain vowel. Suffixes reconstructed for Proto-Turkic, Proto-Mongolic, Proto-Korean, or Proto-Japonic, but not attested in Old Turkic, Classical Mongolian, Middle Korean, or Old Japanese are marked with asterisks.\n\nThis correspondences, however, have been harshly criticized for several reasons: There are significant gaps resulting in the absence of etymologies for certain initial segments: an impossible situation in the case of a genetic relationship; lack of common paradigmatic morphology; in many cases, there are ghosts, invented or polished meanings; and word-list linguistics rules supreme, as there are few if any references to texts or philology.<ref name=georg2004>Stefan Georg (2004): \"[Review of ''Etymological Dictionary of the Altaic Languages'' (2003)]\". ''Diachronica'' volume 21, issue 2, pages 445\u2013450. {{doi|10.1075/dia.21.2.12geo}}</ref><ref name=vovin2011wh>Alexander Vovin (2011): \"[https://www.academia.edu/4208165 Why Japonic is not demonstrably related to 'Altaic' or Korean]\". ''Slides of a talk at the International Conference on Historical Linguistics'' (ICLH XX), Osaka. Accessed on 2019-03-23.</ref>\n\nThere are also many reconstructions proved to be totally false. For instance, regarding Korean, Starostin et al. state that Middle Korean genitive is  /n\u02b2/, while it actually was /s/ in its honorific form, and /\u00f3j/ or /uj/ as neutral forms.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Handbook of Korean Linguistics|last=Jaehoon|first=Yeon|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=449}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, some \"cognates\" are visibly forced, like the comparison between Turkish instrumental {{IPA|-/n/, -/\u026fn/, -/in/}} and Japanese locative /ni/. A locative postposition expresses an absolutely different meaning to that of an instrumental, so it is evident that both of them are not related whatsoever. The same applies for Japanese /ga/ and Proto Tungusic /ga/. The first of those particles expresses genitive case, while the second is the partitive case, which bear no resemblance of meaning at all either.{{dubious|date=December 2019}} A different kind of issue is that of the Old Turkish genitive /X\u014b/ (where \"X\" stands for any phoneme) and Old Japanese genitive /no/. Although they share the same consonant, the fact that the former is a vowel plus a consonant, and the second is a fixed set of the consonant /n/ plus vowel /o/ makes the fact that those two are cognates extremely unlikely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://altaica.ru/LIBRARY/turks/Erdal_OTG.pdf|title=A Grammar of Old Turkic|last=Erdal|first=Marcel|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=29 April 2016}}</ref>{{dubious|date=December 2019}}<!-- not in the source cited -->\n\n===Selected cognates===\n\n====Personal pronouns====\nThe table below is taken (with slight modifications) from Bla\u017eek (2006) and transcribed into IPA.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!\n! Proto-Altaic\n! Proto-Turkic\n! Proto-Mongolic (*), Classical Mongolian\n! Proto-Tungusic\n! Proto-Korean (*), Middle Korean\n! Proto-Japonic\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \"I\" (nominative)\n! {{IPA|/b\u00ec/}}\n| {{IPA|/be/}}\n| {{IPA|*/bi/}}\n| {{IPA|/bi/}}\n| {{IPA|/-i/}}\n| {{IPA|/b\u00e0/}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \"me\" ([[oblique case]]s)\n! {{IPA|/mine/-}}\n| {{IPA|/men/}}\n| {{IPA|*/min/-}}\n| {{IPA|/min/-}}\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \"I\"\n! [[Old Chinese]]: {{IPA|*/\u014ba/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|*/nad/-, -/m/-}} (oblique)\n|\n| {{IPA|/n\u00e0/}} ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \ub098)<br> {{IPA|/\u00fa/}} ([[Sino-Korean vocabulary|Sino-Korean]]: */\u6211/, */\u543e/), {{IPA|yi}} (\u77e3)<sup>1</sup>\n| {{IPA|/a/-}} ([[Sino-Japanese vocabulary|Sino-Japanese]]: */\u6211,\u543e/, '''\u308f'''- \u79c1)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \"[[thou]]\" (nominative)\n! {{IPA|/si/}} and/or {{IPA|/t\u02b0i/}}\n| {{IPA|/se/}} ([[Turkic languages|Turkic]]: Sen, \u0421\u0435\u043d)\n| {{IPA|*/t\u0283i/}} ([[Mongolian language|Mongolian]]: \u0447\u0438)\n| {{IPA|/si/}} ([[Manchu]]: Si, [[Nanai language|Nanai]]: \u0421\u0438)\n| {{IPA|/-si/, /-sya/}}<sup>1</sup>\n| {{IPA|/si/}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \"[[Thou|thee]]\" (oblique cases)\n! {{IPA|/sin/- and/or /t\u02b0in/-}}\n| {{IPA|/sen/}} ([[Turkic languages|Turkic]]: Sen, \u0421\u0435\u043d)\n| ?{{IPA|*/t\u0283in/-}}\n|\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \"thou\"\n! [[Proto-Tibeto-Burman]] {{IPA|/n\u00e1/}}\n| {{IPA|-/\u014b/}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|*/n\u00e8/}} ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \ub108)\n| {{IPA|/n\u00e1/}} ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: \u306a */\u90a3/)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \"we\" (nominative)\n! {{IPA|/b\u00e0/}}\n| {{IPA|/bi-r\u02b2/}} ([[Turkic languages|Turkic]]: Biz, \u0411\u0456\u0437)\n| {{IPA|*/ba/}} ([[Mongolian language|Mongolian]]: \u0411\u0438\u0434)\n| {{IPA|/bue/}} ([[Nanai language|Nanai]]: \u0411\u0443\u044d [[Manchu]]: be)\n| {{IPA|/\u00fa-r\u00ed/}} ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \uc6b0\ub9ac,\uc6b8 */\u4e8e\u5c38/)\n| {{IPA|/b\u00e0/}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \"us\" (oblique cases)\n! {{IPA|/myn/-}}\n|\n| {{IPA|*/man/-}}\n| {{IPA|/myn/-}} ([[Manchu]]: muse)\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \"ye\" (nominative)\n! {{IPA|/sV/}} and/or {{IPA|/t\u02b0V/}}\n| {{IPA|/si-r\u02b2/}} ([[Turkic languages|Turkic]]: Siz, \u0421\u0456\u0437)\n| {{IPA|*/ta/}} ([[Mongolian language|Mongolian]]: \u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0440)\n| {{IPA|/su\u02d0/}} ([[Manchu]]: suwe)\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \"you\" (oblique)\n! {{IPA|/sVn/-}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/sun/-}}\n|\n|\n|}\n\nAs above, forms not attested in Classical Mongolian or Middle Korean but reconstructed for their ancestors are marked with an asterisk, and /V/ represents an uncertain vowel.\n\nThere are, however, several problems with this proposed list. Aside from the huge amount of non-attested, free reconstructions, some mistakes on the research carried out by Altaicists must be pointed out. The first of them is that Old Japanese for the first person pronoun (\"I\", in English) was neither /ba/ or /a/. It was /ware/ (\u548c\u79ae), and sometimes it was abbreviated to /wa/ (\u543e). Also, it is not a Sino-Japanese word, but a native Japanese term. In addition, the second person pronoun was not /si/, but either /imasi/ (\u6c5d), or /namu/ (\u5948\u725f), which sometimes was shortened to /na/. Its plural was /namu tachi/ (\u5948\u725f\u591a\u77e5).<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Descriptive Grammar of Early Old Japanese Prose|last=Bentley|first=John R.|publisher=|year=2001|isbn=|location=|pages=62\u201365}}</ref>\n\n====Other basic vocabulary====\nThe following table is a brief selection of further proposed [[cognate]]s in basic vocabulary across the Altaic family (from Starostin et al. [2003]). Their reconstructions and equivalences are not accepted by the mainstream linguists and therefore remain very controversial.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Proto-Altaic meaning\n! Proto-Altaic\n! Proto-Turkic\n! Proto-Mongolic\n! Proto-Tungusic\n! Proto-Koreanic\n! Proto-Japonic\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! that\n! {{IPA|/t\u02b0a/}}\n| /di/- or /ti/-\n| /te-re/\n| /ta/\n| /tj\u00e9/\n| /tso-re/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! eye\n! {{IPA|/n\u00e6\u0300\u02d0/}}\n|\n| /ni-dy/\n| {{IPA|/n\u02b2ia-sa/}}<sup>5</sup>\n| /n\u00fa-n/\n| /m\u00e0/-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! neck\n! {{IPA|/m\u00f3\u02d0jno/}}\n| {{IPA|/bo\u02d0jn/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|/mo\u014ba-n/}}\n| /mje-k/\n| /n\u0259mpV/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! breast\n! {{IPA|/k\u00f2k\u02b0\u00e8/}}\n| {{IPA|/k\u00f8ky-r\u02b2/}}<sup>1</sup>\n| /k\u00f8k\u00f8-n/<sup>2</sup>\n| /kuku-n/<sup>2</sup>\n| /kokaj\u014bi/ \"pith; medulla; core\"\n| /k\u0259k\u0259-r\u0259/<sup>1</sup> \"heart\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! stone\n! {{IPA|/t\u01ff\u02d0l\u02b2\u00ec/}}\n| {{IPA|/dia\u02d0l\u02b2/}}\n| {{IPA|/t\u0283ila-\u0281u/}}\n| {{IPA|/d\u0292ola/}}\n| {{IPA|/to\u02d0rh/}}<sup>3</sup>\n| {{IPA|/(d)\u00eds\u00ec/}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! star\n! {{IPA|/p\u02b0\u01ffl\u02b2o/}}\n| {{IPA|/jul-dur\u02b2/}}\n| /ho-dun/\n| /osi/<sup>4</sup>\n| {{IPA|/pj\u0268\u02d0r/}}\n| {{IPA|/p\u0259\u0301ts\u00ed/}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! oath, god, sky<ref>{{cite web|url=http://starling.rinet.ru/cgi-bin/response.cgi?single=1&basename=/data/alt/altet&text_number=2306&root=config |title=Altaic etymological database |publisher=Starling.rinet.ru |date= |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n! {{IPA|/t\u00e0\u014b\u0261iri/}}\n| {{IPA|/[[te\u014bri]]/}}\n| /ta\u014bgarag/\n| /ta\u014bgura/\n|\n| {{IPA|/ti\u014bkir/}}\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> Contains the Proto-Altaic dual suffix {{IPA|-/r\u02b2V/}}: \"both breasts\" \u2013 \"chest\" \u2013 \"heart\".<br>\n<sup>2</sup> Contains the Proto-Altaic singulative suffix -/nV/: \"one breast\".<br>\n<sup>3</sup> Compare [[Baekje]] */turak/ \"stone\" (Bla\u017eek 2006).<br>\n<sup>4</sup> This is in the Jurchen language. In modern Manchu it is ''usiha''.<br>\n<sup>5</sup> This is disputed by Georg (2004),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/jbp/dia/2004/00000021/00000002/art00010?token=0058191b9d3ccda7f7e41225f406a5e2c6b4173483f3c255050576b34272c5f7b3d6d3f4e4b34a6eb76ca7f7 |title=Etymological Dictionary of the Altaic Languages (2003) |publisher=Ingentaconnect.com |date=1 January 2004 |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref> who states: \"The traditional Tungusological reconstruction ''*y\u0101sa'' [ = {{IPA|/ja\u02d0sa/}}] cannot be replaced by the nasal-initial one espoused here, needed for the comparison.\" However, Starostin (2005)<ref name=staro2005/> mentions evidence from several Tungusic languages cited by Starostin et al. (2003). Georg (2005) does not accept this, referring to Georg (1999/2000) and a then upcoming paper.<ref name=staro2005>Sergei A. Starostin (2005): \"[http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/jbp/dia/2005/00000022/00000002/art00008?token=00541ba51aae7dd8d6c573d257025255c232b465340514d3874747c4e7547543c7e386f642f466fad2e3 Response to Stefan Georg's review of the ''Etymological Dictionary of the Altaic Languages'']\". ''Diachronica'' volume 22, issue 2, pages 451\u2013454. {{doi|10.1075/dia.22.2.09sta}}</ref>\n\n====Numerals and related words====\nIn the [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European family]], the [[Numeral (linguistics)|numerals]] are remarkably stable. This is a rather exceptional case; especially words for higher numbers are often borrowed wholesale. (Perhaps the most famous cases are [[Japanese numerals|Japanese]] and [[Korean numerals|Korean]], which have two complete sets of numerals each \u2013 one native, one [[Chinese numerals|Chinese]].) Indeed, the Altaic numerals are less stable than the Indo-European ones, but nevertheless Starostin et al. (2003) reconstruct them as follows. They are not accepted by the mainstream linguists and are controversial. Other reconstructions show little to no similarities in numerals of the proto-languages.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Proto-Altaic meaning\n! Proto-Altaic\n! Proto-Turkic\n! Proto-Mongolic\n! Proto-Tungusic\n! Proto-Korean\n! Proto-Japonic\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 1\n! /byri/\n| /bir/\n| /byri/ \"all, each\"\n|\n| {{IPA|/p\u00ecr\u0268\u0301/}} \"at first\"\n| /pi-t\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! single\n! /n\u00f8\u014be/\n| {{IPA|/ja\u014b\u026fr\u02b2/}}\n| /nige/ '''\"1\"'''\n| /no\u014b/~/non/ \"be the first, begin\"\n|\n| /n\u0259mi/ \"only\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! front\n! /emo/\n| /\u00f8m-gen/ \"upper part of breast\"\n| /emy/-\n| /emu/~/ume/ '''\"1\"'''\n| /maen-/~/m\u00f4n-ch\u00f4/ \"first of all\"<sup>26</sup>\n| /upe/ \"upper\"<br> /mape/ \"front\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! single, one of a pair\n! {{IPA|/s\u01ffna/}}\n| {{IPA|/s\u026f\u014bar/}} \"one of a pair\"\n| /son-du-/ \"odd\"\n| <sup>1</sup>\n| {{IPA|/h\u0259\u0300n\u00e0h/}} '''\"1\"'''<br> or /h\u0259\u0300t-/ <sup>1</sup>\n| /sa/- \"together, reciprocally\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 2\n! /tybu/\n| <sup>2</sup>\n| {{IPA|/d\u0292iw-rin/~/d\u0292ui-rin/}} \"2 (feminine)\"<sup>3</sup>\n| {{IPA|/d\u0292ube/}}\n| {{IPA|/tu\u02d0/, /tu\u02d0-rh/}}<sup>4</sup>\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! pair, couple\n! {{IPA|/p\u02b0\u00f8\u0300k\u02b0e/}}\n| /eki/ '''\"2\"''', {{IPA|/ekir\u02b2/}} \"twins\"; ?{{IPA|/(j)\u025b\u0261ir-mi/}} \"20\"\n| /(h)ekire/ \"twins\"\n|\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! different, other\n! /gojV/\n|\n| /gojar/ '''\"2\"'''\n| /goj/~/gia/\n|\n| /k\u00eda/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! pair, half\n! {{IPA|/put\u0283\u02b0u/}}\n| {{IPA|/but\u0283-uk/}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/pt\u0283a-k/}}\n| /puta/- '''\"2\"'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 3\n! /\u014by/\n| {{IPA|/o-tur\u02b2/}} \"30\"<sup>5</sup>\n| /gu-rban/; {{IPA|/\u0261u-t\u0283in/}} \"30\"\n|\n| <sup>6</sup>\n| /mi/-<sup>7</sup>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! <sup>(footnote 8)</sup>\n! /\u00ecl\u00f9/\n| /\u00f8l\u00f8\u014b/<sup>9</sup>\n|\n| /ila-n/ '''\"3\"'''\n|/j\u0259r\u0259/ \"many\"\n| /\u00f9r\u00f9-pu/ \"bissextile (year or month)\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! object consisting of 3 parts\n! /s\u00e9jra/\n|\n| {{IPA|/sere-\u0281e/}} \"trident, pitchfork\"\n|\n| {{IPA|/se\u02d0i(h)/}} '''\"3\"'''\n| /s\u00e1r\u00e1pi/ \"rake, pitchfork\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 4\n! {{IPA|/to\u02d0jV/}}\n| {{IPA|/d\u00f8\u02d0-rt/}}\n| /d\u00f8-rben/; {{IPA|/d\u00f8-rt\u0283in/}} \"40\"<sup>10</sup>\n| /dy-gin/\n|\n| /d\u0259/-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 5\n! {{IPA|/t\u02b0u/}}\n|\n| /ta-bun/; /ta-bin/ \"50\"<sup>11</sup>\n| {{IPA|/tu-n\u02b2\u0261a/}}\n| /t\u00e0/-\n| /i-tu-/<sup>12</sup>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 6\n! {{IPA|/n\u02b2u/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|/d\u0292i-r\u0261u-/}}; {{IPA|/d\u0292i-ran/}} \"60\"<sup>13</sup>\n| {{IPA|/n\u02b2u-\u014bu-/}}\n| <sup>14</sup>\n| /mu/-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 7\n! {{IPA|/nadi/}}<sup>15</sup>\n| /jeti/\n| {{IPA|/dolu-\u0281an/}}; /dala-n/ \"70\"<sup>15</sup>\n| /nada-n/\n| /n\u00ecr-(k\u00fap)/<sup>16</sup>\n| /nana/-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 8\n! {{IPA|/d\u0292a/}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/d\u0292a-pkun/}}\n| /j\u00e8-t-/<sup>17</sup>\n| /da/-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 9\n! {{IPA|/k\u02b0e\u0261VnV/}}\n|\n|\n| /xegyn/\n|\n| /k\u0259k\u0259n\u0259/\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 10\n! {{IPA|/t\u0283\u00f8be/}} or /t\u00f8be/\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/d\u0292uba-n/}}\n|\n| /t\u0259w\u0259/<sup>18</sup>,/-so/\"-0\"/i-so/50\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | many, a big number\n! {{IPA|/d\u0292\u00f8\u02d0r\u02b2o/}}\n| {{IPA|/jy\u02d0r\u02b2/}} \"100\"\n|\n| <sup>19</sup>\n| /j\u00e9r(h)/ \"10\"  /j\u0259\u0300r\u0259\u0300/ \"many\"\n| {{IPA|/j\u0259\u0300r\u0259\u0300/-}} \"10,000\"<br> /j\u0259\u0300r\u0259\u0300/ \"many\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! {{IPA|/p\u02b0VbV/}}\n| {{IPA|/o\u02d0-n/}} '''\"10\"'''\n| /ha-rban/ '''\"10\"''', /ha-na/ \"all\"\n| <sup>20</sup>\n|\n| -/p\u0259/, -/pua/ \"-00\"<sup>21</sup>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 20\n! {{IPA|/k\u02b0yra/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0261\u026frk/}} or {{IPA|/k\u026frk/}} \"40\"<sup>22</sup>\n| /kori-n/\n| /xori-n/\n|\n| /pata-ti/<sup>23</sup>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 100\n! {{IPA|/n\u02b2\u00e0m\u00f2/}}\n| ?/jom/ \"big number, all\"\n| {{IPA|/d\u0292a\u0281u-n/}}<sup>24</sup>\n| {{IPA|/n\u02b2ama\u02d0/}}\n|\n| {{IPA|/mu\u00e0mu\u00e0/}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! 1000\n! {{IPA|/t\u0283\u1ef3mi/}}\n| /dymen/ or /tymen/ \"10,000\"<sup>25</sup>\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|/t\u0283\u0268\u0300m\u0268\u0300n/}}\n| /ti/\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> [[Manchu language|Manchu]] /soni/ \"single, odd\".<br>\n<sup>2</sup> [[Bulgar language|Old Bulgarian]] /tvi-rem/ \"second\".<br>\n<sup>3</sup> [[Khitan language|Kitan]] has {{IPA|/t\u0283ur/}} '''\"2\"''' (Bla\u017eek 2006).<br>\n<sup>4</sup> {{IPA|-/u\u02d0/-}} is probably a contraction of -/ubu/-.<br>\n<sup>5</sup> The /y/- of {{IPA|/yt\u0283/}} \"3\" \"may also reflect the same root, although the suffixation is not clear.\" (Starostin et al. 2003:223)<br>\n<sup>6</sup> Compare [[Silla]] /mir/ \"3\" (Bla\u017eek 2006).<br>\n<sup>7</sup> Compare [[Goguryeo language|Goguryeo]] /mir/ \"3\" (Bla\u017eek 2006).<br>\n<sup>8</sup> \"third (or next after three = fourth)\", \"consisting of three objects\"<br>\n<sup>9</sup> \"song with three out of four verses rhyming (first, second and fourth)\"<br>\n<sup>10</sup> Kitan has {{IPA|/dur/}} '''\"4\"''' (Bla\u017eek 2006).<br>\n<sup>11</sup> Kitan has {{IPA|/tau/}} '''\"5\"''' (Bla\u017eek 2006).<br>\n<sup>12</sup> \"(the prefixed i- is somewhat unclear: it is also used as a separate word meaning 'fifty', but the historical root here is no doubt ''*tu-'')\" (Starostin et al. 2003:223). \u2013 Bla\u017eek (2006) also considers Goguryeo {{IPA|*/uts/}} '''\"5\"''' (from {{IPA|*/uti/}}) to be related.<br>\n<sup>13</sup> Kitan has {{IPA|/nir/}} '''\"6\"''' (Bla\u017eek 2006).<br>\n<sup>14</sup> Middle Korean has {{IPA|/je-(s\u0268s)/}} \"6\", which may fit here, but the required loss of initial {{IPA|/n\u02b2/-}} \"is not quite regular\" (Starostin et al. 2003:224).<br>\n<sup>15</sup> The Mongolian forms \"may suggest an original proto-form\" {{IPA|/l\u02b2adi/}} or {{IPA|/ladi/}} \"with [[dissimilation]] or [[Metathesis (linguistics)|metathesis]] in\" Proto-Mongolic (Starostin et al. 2003:224). \u2013 Kitan has {{IPA|/dol/}} '''\"7\"'''.<br>\n<sup>16</sup> {{IPA|/\u0256irkup/}}{{citation needed|date=April 2011}} in Early [[Middle Korean]] (\u30bf\u30ea\u30af\u30cb/\u30c1\u30ea\u30af\u30d2 in the ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Nich\u016breki|ja|3=\u4e8c\u4e2d\u6b74}}'').<br>\n<sup>17</sup> \"Problematic\" (Starostin et al. 2003:224).<br>\n<sup>18</sup> Compare Goguryeo {{IPA|/tok/}} \"10\" (Bla\u017eek 2006).<br>\n<sup>19</sup> Manchu {{IPA|/d\u0292iri/, /d\u0292irun/}} \"a very big number\".<br>\n<sup>20</sup> [[Orok language|Orok]] {{IPA|/po\u02d0wo/}} \"a bundle of 10 squirrels\", [[Nanai language|Nanai]] {{IPA|/po\u00e3/}} \"collection, gathering\".<br>\n<sup>21</sup> \"Hundred\" in names of hundreds.<br>\n<sup>22</sup> Starostin et al. (2003) suspect this to be a reduplication: {{IPA|*/k\u026fr-k\u026fr/}} \"20 + 20\".<br>\n<sup>23</sup> {{IPA|/kata-ti/}} would be expected; Starostin et al. (2003) think that this irregular change from {{IPA|/k/}} to {{IPA|/p/}} is due to influence from \"2\" {{IPA|/puta-tu/}}.<br>\n<sup>24</sup> From {{IPA|*/n\u02b2am-\u014bu-/}}.<br>\n<sup>25</sup> Also see [[Tumen (unit)|T\u00fcmen]].<br>\n<sup>26</sup> Modern Korean \u2013 needs further investigations\n\n==See also==\n*[[Classification of the Japonic languages]]\n*[[Nostratic languages]]\n*[[Uralo-Siberian languages]]\n*[[Xiongnu]]\n*[[Pan-Turanism]]\n*[[Turco-Mongol]] \n*[[Yeniseian languages]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Works cited ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Aalto, Pentti. 1955. \"On t