{"title_page": "Flag of the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{hatnote|The history, current status and nomenclature of the Union Jack, and its use other than as a flag for the United Kingdom, are covered more fully under the article ''[[Union Jack]]''.}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox flag\n| Name = United Kingdom of<br>Great Britain and Northern Ireland\n| Article = the\n| Nickname = [[Union Jack]], Union Flag, British flag, UK flag\n| Image = Flag of the United Kingdom.svg\n| Use = 111000\n| Symbol =\n| Proportion = 1:2\n| Adoption = {{Start date and age|1801|1|1|df=y}}\n| Design = A white-fimbriated symmetric red cross on a blue field with a white-fimbriated counterchanged saltire of red and white.\n| Image2 = Civil Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg\n| Use2 = 000100\n| Proportion2 = 1:2\n| Design2 = A red field with the Union Flag in the canton. See [[Red Ensign]].\n| Image3 = Government Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg\n| Use3 = 00010\n| Proportion3 = 1:2\n| Design3 = A blue field with the Union Flag in the canton. See [[Blue Ensign]].\n| Image4 = Naval Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg\n| Name4 = Saint George's Ensign\n| Use4 = 000001\n| Proportion4 = 1:2\n| Design4 = A symmetric red cross on a white field with the Union Flag in the canton. See [[White Ensign]].\n| Use5 = Air Force Ensign\n| Image5 = Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg\n| Name5 = [[Royal Air Force Ensign]]\n| Proportion5 = 1:2\n| Design5 = A field of air force blue with the Union Flag in the canton and the [[Royal Air Force roundels|RAF roundel]] in the middle of the fly.\n}}\n\nThe '''national flag of the United Kingdom''' is the '''Union Jack''', also known as the '''Union Flag'''.<ref>[http://www.flaginstitute.org/wp/british-flags/the-union-jack-or-the-union-flag/ The Flag Institute]: \"It is often stated that the Union Flag should only be described as the Union Jack when flown in the bows of a warship, but this is a relatively recent idea. From early in its life the Admiralty itself frequently referred to the flag as the Union Jack, whatever its use, and in 1902 an Admiralty Circular announced that Their Lordships had decided that either name could be used officially. Such use was given Parliamentary approval in 1908 when it was stated that 'the Union Jack should be regarded as the National flag'.\"</ref>\n\nThe current design of the Union Jack dates from the [[Act of Union 1801]] which united the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] and the [[Kingdom of Ireland]] (previously in [[personal union]]) to create the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]. The flag consists of the [[St George's Cross|red cross]] of [[Saint George]] ([[patron saint]] of [[England]]), edged in white, superimposed on the [[Saint Patrick's Flag|Cross of]] [[St Patrick]] (patron saint of [[Ireland]]), which are superimposed on the [[Flag of Scotland|Saltire]] of [[Saint Andrew]] (patron saint of [[Scotland]]). [[Wales]] is not represented in the Union Flag by Wales's patron saint, [[Saint David]], as at the time the flag was designed Wales was part of the [[Kingdom of England]].\n\nThe flag's standard height-to-length proportions are 1:2.<ref name=\"Flag propartions\">[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/614768/United-Kingdom-flag-of-the/ United Kingdom, flag of the], for flag ratio see flag caption</ref> The [[war flag]] variant used by the [[British Army]] modifies the proportions to 3:5 and crops two of the red diagonals.\n\nThe earlier [[flag of Great Britain]] was established in 1606 by a [[proclamation]] of [[James I of England|King James VI and I]] of [[List of Scottish monarchs|Scotland]] and [[List of English monarchs|England]].<ref>[[Arthur Charles Fox-Davies|A.C. Fox-Davies]], ''[[The Art of Heraldry: An Encyclop\u00e6dia of Armory]]'' (1904, reprinted 1986, {{ISBN|0-906223-34-2}}), p. 399: \"By the King: Whereas, some differences hath arisen between Our subjects of South and North Britaine travelling by Seas, about the bearing of their Flagges: For the avoiding of all contentions hereafter. We have, with the advice of our Council, ordered: That from henceforth all our Subjects of this Isle and [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Kingdome of Great Britaine]], and all our members thereof, shall beare in their main-toppe the [[Flag of England|Red Crosse]], commonly called [[St George's Cross|St George's Crosse]], and the [[Flag of Scotland|White Crosse]], commonly called [[Flag of Scotland|St Andrew's Crosse]], joyned together according to the forme made by our [[herald]]s, and sent by Us to our Admerall to be published to our Subjects: and in their fore-toppe our Subjects of South Britaine shall weare the Red Crosse onely as they were wont, and our Subjects of North Britaine in their fore-toppe the White Crosse onely as they were accustomed\"|James VI and I|[[Orders in Council]]; Official creation of the Union Flag \u2013 1606.\"</ref> The new flag of the United Kingdom was officially created by an [[Order in Council]] of 1801, reading as follows:\n{{Quote|The Union Flag shall be [[Azure (heraldry)|azure]], the Crosses [[saltire]] of Saint Andrew and Saint Patrick quarterly per saltire, counter-changed, [[argent]] and [[gules]], the latter [[fimbriation|fimbriated]] of the [[argent|second]], surmounted by the Cross of Saint George of the [[gules|third]] fimbriated as the saltire.<ref>Max Cryer, ''Curious English Words and Phrases: The Truth Behind the Expressions We Use'' (2012), p. 395: \"When Britain's official flag settled down in 1801, its exact design and colouring were meticulously written out by Order of Council which described it as 'the Union Flag'... The correct formal wording of the Order of Council, 1801, was...\" &c.</ref>}}\n\n==Flying the flag==\n{{image frame\n|border=no\n|content={{Union Jack evolution}}\n|link=Template:Union Jack evolution\n|link_text=Bigger Render\n|caption=Evolution of the Union flag}}\n\nThe Union Flag can be flown by any individual or organisation in Great Britain on any day of their choice. Legal regulations restrict the use of the [[Union Jack|Union Flag]] on Government buildings in [[Northern Ireland]]. Long-standing restrictions on Government use of the flag elsewhere were abolished in July 2007.<ref name=\"dcms\">[[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]]: ''[http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/ Flag Flying]''</ref><ref name=\"gob\">[http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/cm71/7170/7170.pdf The Governance of Britain], for flying the Union Flag, see pp. 57\u201358</ref>\n\n===Upside-down===\nWhile the flag appears symmetric, the white lines above and below the diagonal red are different widths. On the side closer to the flagpole (or on the left when depicted on paper), the white lines above the diagonals are wider; on the side farther from the flagpole (or on the right when depicted on paper), the converse is true. Thus, no change will be apparent when rotating the flag 180 degrees, but if mirrored the flag will be upside-down.\n\nPlacing the flag upside down is considered [[l\u00e8se majest\u00e9]] and is offensive to some.<ref>Matthew Tempest and agencies  [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2004/jan/19/northernireland.devolution Paisley to stand down as MEP], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 19 January 2004. \"After receiving almost 30% of the overall Northern Ireland vote in the 1979 European election, [[Ian Paisley]] became the first MEP to speak in the parliament when he protested that the Union Flag was flying upside down.\"</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/politics/29213.stm Defence Secretary apologises for flag blunder] BBC News, 13 November 1997</ref> However, it can be flown upside down as a distress signal. While this is rare, it was used by groups under siege during the [[Boer War]] and during campaigns in India in the late 18th century. {{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n===St Patrick's saltire===\nBecause of the relative positions of the saltires of St Patrick and St Andrew, the UK flag is not symmetrical. The red saltire of St Patrick is offset such that it does not relegate the white saltire of St Andrew to a mere border. St my andrew sucke off britnay\n\n===Half-mast===\nThe Union Flag is flown from Government buildings at [[half-mast]] in the following situations:<ref>[http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/faqs.html ''FAQ''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016132137/http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/faqs.html |date=16 October 2008 }} [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]]</ref>\n*from the announcement of the death of the [[British monarch|Sovereign]] <!-- until when, indefinitely? --> (an exception is made for [[Proclamation Day]] \u2013 the day the new Sovereign is proclaimed, when the Flag is flown at full mast from 11&nbsp;am to sunset)\n*the day of the funeral of a member of the [[British Royal Family]]\n*the funeral of a foreign Head of State\n*the funeral of a former [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]]\n\nThe Sovereign sometimes declares other days when the Union Flag is to fly at [[half-mast]]. Half-mast means the flag is flown two-thirds of the way up the flagpole with at least the height of the flag between the top of the flag and the top of the flagpole.<ref>[http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/faqs.html#3 ''FAQ: What is half mast?''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016132137/http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/faqs.html |date=16 October 2008 }} [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]]</ref>\n\n== Flying from public buildings ==\nUntil July 2007, the Union Flag was only flown on Government buildings on a limited number of special days each year. The choice of days was managed by the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] (DCMS).<ref name=\"dcms\" /> Government buildings are those used by civil servants, [[the Crown]], or the armed forces. They were not applicable to private citizens, corporations, or local authorities.<ref name=\"dcms\" />\n\nOn 3 July 2007, the [[Secretary of State for Justice|Justice Secretary]] [[Jack Straw]] laid a [[green paper]] before Parliament entitled ''The Governance of Britain''.<ref name=\"gob\" /> Alongside a range of proposed changes to the constitutional arrangements of the UK was a specific announcement that there would be consultation on whether the rules on flag-flying on Government buildings should be relaxed.\n\nTwo days later, Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] announced that with immediate effect the Union Flag would fly from the flag pole above the front entrance of [[10 Downing Street]] on every day of the year. The intention was to increase feelings of [[British national identity]]. Other Government departments were asked to follow this lead, and all Government buildings in Whitehall did so.<ref>[http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page12378.asp Morning Press Briefing] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809013048/http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page12378.asp |date=9 August 2007 }} by [[Prime Minister's Spokesman]], 6 July 2007</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/07/07/nflag107.xml Union flag already flying all year round] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' 7 July 2007</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6276280.stm Brown lifts ban on national flag] BBC News, 6 July 2007</ref><ref>[http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/news/archives/2007/07/06/brown_flies_flag_for_britain.html Brown flies flag for Britain] ''[[The Guardian]]'' 6 July 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article2034055.ece \"Union Jack will fly over No 10 permanently 'to show values'\"]. ''[[The Times]]'' 6 July 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-23403148-details/Whitehall+flies+the+flag+in+boost+for+Britishness/article.do \"Gordon orders Whitehall to fly the flag in boost for Britishness\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090819090145/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-23403148-details/Whitehall+flies+the+flag+in+boost+for+Britishness/article.do |date=19 August 2009 }} ''[[Evening Standard]]'' 6 July 2007</ref>\n\n[[James Purnell]], [[Culture Secretary]] from June 2007 to January 2008 in Brown's administration, subsequently concurred with the abolition of the restrictions \u2013 pending consultation on longer term arrangements.\n\n===Flag days===\nThe flag days directed by the DCMS include birthdays of members of the [[British Royal Family|Royal Family]], the wedding anniversary of the Monarch, [[Commonwealth Day]], [[Accession Day]], [[Coronation Day]], [[Queen's Birthday|The Queen's official birthday]], [[Remembrance Sunday]] and on the days of the [[State Opening of Parliament|State Opening]] and [[legislative session#Procedure in Commonwealth realms|prorogation]] of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]].\n\nSince the beginning of 2013, the relevant days have been:\n\n* 9 January: birthday of [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|The Duchess of Cambridge]]\n* 20 January: birthday of [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|The Countess of Wessex]]\n* 6 February: anniversary of [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]]'s accession in 1952\n* 19 February: birthday of [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|The Duke of York]]\n* Second Sunday in March: [[Commonwealth Day]]\n* 10 March: birthday of [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|The Earl of Wessex]]\n* 21 April: The Queen's birthday\n* 9 May: [[Europe Day]]\n* 2 June: anniversary of The Queen's 1953 [[Coronation Day|coronation]]\n* 10 June: birthday of [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n* A Saturday in June: [[Queen's Birthday|The Queen's Official Birthday]]\n* 21 June: birthday of [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|The Duke of Cambridge]]\n* 17 July: birthday of [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|The Duchess of Cornwall]]\n* 15 August: birthday of [[Anne, Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]]\n* Second Sunday in November: [[Remembrance Sunday]]\n* 14 November: birthday of [[Charles, Prince of Wales|The Prince of Wales]]\n* 20 November: anniversary of the wedding of The Queen and The Duke of Edinburgh\n\nIn addition, the flag should be flown in the following areas on the specified days:\n* [[Wales]] \u2013 1 March: [[Saint David's Day]]\n* [[Northern Ireland]] \u2013 17 March: [[Saint Patrick's Day]]\n* [[England]] \u2013 23 April: [[Saint George's Day]]\n* [[Scotland]] \u2013 30 November: [[Saint Andrew's Day]]\n* [[Greater London]]: The day of the opening or proroguing of Parliament\n\nSome non-central government bodies still continue to follow the flag days.\n\nIn Scotland, the [[Scottish Government]] has decreed that the [[Flag of Scotland]] (\"the Saltire\") will fly on all its buildings every day from 8&nbsp;am until sunset, but there is no specific policy on flying the Union Flag and as such it is sometimes flown alongside the Saltire and sometimes omitted. An exception is made for \"national days\". On these days, the Saltire shall be lowered and replaced with the Union Flag. These are the same as the flag days noted above with the exception of:\n* 3 September: [[Merchant Navy]] Day\n\nAnother difference is that on [[Saint Andrew's Day]], the Union Flag can only be flown if the building has more than one flagpole \u2013 the Saltire will not be lowered to make way for the Union Flag if there is only one flagpole.<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/People/royal-ceremonial \"Royal and ceremonial\"] [[Scottish Government]]</ref>\n[[File:British Airways tails lined up at LHR Terminal 5B Iwelumo.jpg|thumb|upright=1.14| The flag on British airways parked at [[London Heathrow Airport]]]]\n\n===Northern Ireland===\nIn [[Northern Ireland]], the Union Flag is flown from buildings of the [[Northern Ireland Office]] as decreed by Regulations published in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/sr/sr2000/20000347.htm |title=The Flags Regulations (Northern Ireland) 2000 |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |accessdate=2010-06-14}}</ref> The Regulations were amended in 2002 to remove the requirement to fly the flag on the birthdays of [[Queen Elizabeth, the Queen Mother]] and [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon]] who both died that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/Sr/sr2003/20030553.htm |title=The Flags Regulations (Northern Ireland) (Amendment) 2002 |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |accessdate=2010-06-14}}</ref> The current flag days are now the same as the United Kingdom government days noted above with the exception of the Duchess of Cornwall's birthday, which was only added to the UK flag days after her wedding to the Prince of Wales in 2005, and has not yet been extended to Northern Ireland.\n\nThe [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]] is the only body in the United Kingdom that is not permitted to fly the Union Flag, and is only permitted to fly its service flag or the [[Royal Standard (United Kingdom)|Royal Standard]] in the event of a visit by the Sovereign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/Sr/sr2002/20020023.htm |title=Police Emblems and Flags Regulations (Northern Ireland) 2002 |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |accessdate=2010-06-14}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed redesigns==\n\n=== Suggested incorporation of the Welsh dragon ===\n[[File:Union Flag (including Wales).svg|thumb|One suggested redesign of the Union Jack with the red dragon from the [[flag of Wales]] added in the centre]]\nIn November 2007 the then culture minister [[Margaret Hodge]] said she would consider a redesign of the Union Flag to incorporate the [[Welsh dragon]], during a debate in the House of Commons on the frequency with which the flag flies above public buildings. The issue was initially raised by [[Ian Lucas]], another [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP, who complained that the flag introduced in 1606 following the accession of [[James VI of Scotland]] to the English throne as James I combined the cross of St George and the saltire of St Andrew. This principle continued in 1801 when the St Patrick cross was incorporated following the [[Union with Ireland Act 1800]]. Lucas claimed the identity of [[Wales]] had been suppressed ever since the [[Laws in Wales Acts 1535\u20131542]]. In the debate, [[Albert Owen]] MP said that \"we in Wales do not feel part of the union flag because the dragon or the [[Flag of Saint David|cross of St David]] is not on it.\"<ref name=guardian>Wintour, Patrick (28 November 2007). [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/nov/28/uk.britishidentity  \"Minister proposes a redesign for the union flag\"], ''The Guardian''</ref> [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP [[Stewart Jackson]] described the comments as \"eccentric\".<ref name=telegraph>Cleland, Gary (27 November 2007). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/1570613/Union-Jack-should-include-Welsh-flag-says-MP.html \"Union Jack should include Welsh flag, says MP\"], ''Daily Telegraph''</ref>\n\n=== Scottish independence ===\nAs of 2013, numerous proposals were made about how the Union Flag might be altered to create a flag for the union of England, Wales and Northern Ireland after possible [[Scottish independence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-25205017|title=What would the union jack look like if the Scottish bit was removed?|publisher=BBC News|author=Sam Judah|date=4 December 2013}}</ref> The [[College of Arms]] stated that there would be no need to change the flag in those circumstances, and the existing flag could continue to be used if desired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2013-11-26/no-plans-to-change-union-flag/|title=Union Flag: What happens if Scotland wins independence?|date=27 November 2013|publisher=ITV News}}</ref> Regarding the removal of Scottish heraldic features from the Union Flag, the [[Court of the Lord Lyon]] stated in 2012 that \"[that] would be speculation at this stage, and we could only cross that bridge if we came to it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/would-the-blue-have-to-be-taken-out-of-union-1128610|title=Would the blue have to be taken out of Union flag if Scotland became independent?|publisher=Daily Record|date=7 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Flags of the Interregnum (British Isles)#Flags of the Commonwealth|Commonwealth's flags]]\n* [[Flag Institute]]\n* [[Historical flags of the British Empire and the overseas territories]]\n* [[List of British flags|List of flags of the United Kingdom]] \u2013 a list of flags used within the United Kingdom, the Crown Dependencies and the British overseas territories.\n** [[List of English flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within England\n*** [[List of Cornish flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within [[Cornwall]]\n** [[List of Northern Irish flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within Northern Ireland\n** [[List of Scottish flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within Scotland\n** [[List of Welsh flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within Wales\n* [[List of flags of the Republic of Ireland|List of Irish flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within the Republic of Ireland\n* [[National colours of the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Protectorate Jack]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Flags of the United Kingdom}}\n* {{FOTW|id=gb|title=United Kingdom}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130630062430/https://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx British Monarchy \u2013 Union Flag]\n* [http://www.flaginstitute.org The Flag Institute]\n* [http://bristolgrenadiers.org/colours/colours.htm British Armed forces Grenadiers Colour]\n\n{{-}}\n{{UKFlags}}\n{{Flag of Europe}}\n{{Union Flag}}\n\n[[Category:Flags of the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:National flags|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:National symbols of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Unionism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Flags with crosses|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Flags introduced in 1801|United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|The history, current status and nomenclature of the Union Jack, and its use other than as a flag for the United Kingdom, are covered more fully under the article ''[[Union Jack]]''.}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox flag\n| Name = United Kingdom of<br>Great Britain and Northern Ireland\n| Article = the\n| Nickname = [[Union Jack]], Union Flag, British flag, UK flag\n| Image = Flag of the United Kingdom.svg\n| Use = 111000\n| Symbol =\n| Proportion = 1:2\n| Adoption = {{Start date and age|1801|1|1|df=y}}\n| Design = A white-fimbriated symmetric red cross on a blue field with a white-fimbriated counterchanged saltire of red and white.\n| Image2 = Civil Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg\n| Use2 = 000100\n| Proportion2 = 1:2\n| Design2 = A red field with the Union Flag in the canton. See [[Red Ensign]].\n| Image3 = Government Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg\n| Use3 = 00010\n| Proportion3 = 1:2\n| Design3 = A blue field with the Union Flag in the canton. See [[Blue Ensign]].\n| Image4 = Naval Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg\n| Name4 = Saint George's Ensign\n| Use4 = 000001\n| Proportion4 = 1:2\n| Design4 = A symmetric red cross on a white field with the Union Flag in the canton. See [[White Ensign]].\n| Use5 = Air Force Ensign\n| Image5 = Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg\n| Name5 = [[Royal Air Force Ensign]]\n| Proportion5 = 1:2\n| Design5 = A field of air force blue with the Union Flag in the canton and the [[Royal Air Force roundels|RAF roundel]] in the middle of the fly.\n}}\n\nThe '''national flag of the United Kingdom''' is the '''Union Jack''', also known as the '''Union Flag'''.<ref>[http://www.flaginstitute.org/wp/british-flags/the-union-jack-or-the-union-flag/ The Flag Institute]: \"It is often stated that the Union Flag should only be described as the Union Jack when flown in the bows of a warship, but this is a relatively recent idea. From early in its life the Admiralty itself frequently referred to the flag as the Union Jack, whatever its use, and in 1902 an Admiralty Circular announced that Their Lordships had decided that either name could be used officially. Such use was given Parliamentary approval in 1908 when it was stated that 'the Union Jack should be regarded as the National flag'.\"</ref>\n\nThe current design of the Union Jack dates from the [[Act of Union 1801]] which united the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] and the [[Kingdom of Ireland]] (previously in [[personal union]]) to create the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]. The flag consists of the [[St George's Cross|red cross]] of [[Saint George]] ([[patron saint]] of [[England]]), edged in white, superimposed on the [[Saint Patrick's Flag|Cross of]] [[St Patrick]] (patron saint of [[Ireland]]), which are superimposed on the [[Flag of Scotland|Saltire]] of [[Saint Andrew]] (patron saint of [[Scotland]]). [[Wales]] is not represented in the Union Flag by Wales's patron saint, [[Saint David]], as at the time the flag was designed Wales was part of the [[Kingdom of England]].\n\nThe flag's standard height-to-length proportions are 1:2.<ref name=\"Flag propartions\">[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/614768/United-Kingdom-flag-of-the/ United Kingdom, flag of the], for flag ratio see flag caption</ref> The [[war flag]] variant used by the [[British Army]] modifies the proportions to 3:5 and crops two of the red diagonals.\n\nThe earlier [[flag of Great Britain]] was established in 1606 by a [[proclamation]] of [[James I of England|King James VI and I]] of [[List of Scottish monarchs|Scotland]] and [[List of English monarchs|England]].<ref>[[Arthur Charles Fox-Davies|A.C. Fox-Davies]], ''[[The Art of Heraldry: An Encyclop\u00e6dia of Armory]]'' (1904, reprinted 1986, {{ISBN|0-906223-34-2}}), p. 399: \"By the King: Whereas, some differences hath arisen between Our subjects of South and North Britaine travelling by Seas, about the bearing of their Flagges: For the avoiding of all contentions hereafter. We have, with the advice of our Council, ordered: That from henceforth all our Subjects of this Isle and [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Kingdome of Great Britaine]], and all our members thereof, shall beare in their main-toppe the [[Flag of England|Red Crosse]], commonly called [[St George's Cross|St George's Crosse]], and the [[Flag of Scotland|White Crosse]], commonly called [[Flag of Scotland|St Andrew's Crosse]], joyned together according to the forme made by our [[herald]]s, and sent by Us to our Admerall to be published to our Subjects: and in their fore-toppe our Subjects of South Britaine shall weare the Red Crosse onely as they were wont, and our Subjects of North Britaine in their fore-toppe the White Crosse onely as they were accustomed\"|James VI and I|[[Orders in Council]]; Official creation of the Union Flag \u2013 1606.\"</ref> The new flag of the United Kingdom was officially created by an [[Order in Council]] of 1801, reading as follows:\n{{Quote|The Union Flag shall be [[Azure (heraldry)|azure]], the Crosses [[saltire]] of Saint Andrew and Saint Patrick quarterly per saltire, counter-changed, [[argent]] and [[gules]], the latter [[fimbriation|fimbriated]] of the [[argent|second]], surmounted by the Cross of Saint George of the [[gules|third]] fimbriated as the saltire.<ref>Max Cryer, ''Curious English Words and Phrases: The Truth Behind the Expressions We Use'' (2012), p. 395: \"When Britain's official flag settled down in 1801, its exact design and colouring were meticulously written out by Order of Council which described it as 'the Union Flag'... The correct formal wording of the Order of Council, 1801, was...\" &c.</ref>}}\n\n==Flying the flag==\n{{image frame\n|border=no\n|content={{Union Jack evolution}}\n|link=Template:Union Jack evolution\n|link_text=Bigger Render\n|caption=Evolution of the Union flag}}\n\nThe Union Flag can be flown by any individual or organisation in Great Britain on any day of their choice. Legal regulations restrict the use of the [[Union Jack|Union Flag]] on Government buildings in [[Northern Ireland]]. Long-standing restrictions on Government use of the flag elsewhere were abolished in July 2007.<ref name=\"dcms\">[[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]]: ''[http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/ Flag Flying]''</ref><ref name=\"gob\">[http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/cm71/7170/7170.pdf The Governance of Britain], for flying the Union Flag, see pp. 57\u201358</ref>\n\n===Upside-down===\nWhile the flag appears symmetric, the white lines above and below the diagonal red are different widths. On the side closer to the flagpole (or on the left when depicted on paper), the white lines above the diagonals are wider; on the side farther from the flagpole (or on the right when depicted on paper), the converse is true. Thus, no change will be apparent when rotating the flag 180 degrees, but if mirrored the flag will be upside-down.\n\nPlacing the flag upside down is considered [[l\u00e8se majest\u00e9]] and is offensive to some.<ref>Matthew Tempest and agencies  [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2004/jan/19/northernireland.devolution Paisley to stand down as MEP], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 19 January 2004. \"After receiving almost 30% of the overall Northern Ireland vote in the 1979 European election, [[Ian Paisley]] became the first MEP to speak in the parliament when he protested that the Union Flag was flying upside down.\"</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/politics/29213.stm Defence Secretary apologises for flag blunder] BBC News, 13 November 1997</ref> However, it can be flown upside down as a distress signal. While this is rare, it was used by groups under siege during the [[Boer War]] and during campaigns in India in the late 18th century. {{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n===St Patrick's saltire===\nBecause of the relative positions of the saltires of St Patrick and St Andrew, the UK flag is not symmetrical. The red saltire of St Patrick is offset such that it does not relegate the white saltire of St Andrew to a mere border. St Andrew's saltire has the higher position at the hoist side with St Patrick's saltire in the higher position on the opposite side.\n\n===Half-mast===\nThe Union Flag is flown from Government buildings at [[half-mast]] in the following situations:<ref>[http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/faqs.html ''FAQ''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016132137/http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/faqs.html |date=16 October 2008 }} [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]]</ref>\n*from the announcement of the death of the [[British monarch|Sovereign]] <!-- until when, indefinitely? --> (an exception is made for [[Proclamation Day]] \u2013 the day the new Sovereign is proclaimed, when the Flag is flown at full mast from 11&nbsp;am to sunset)\n*the day of the funeral of a member of the [[British Royal Family]]\n*the funeral of a foreign Head of State\n*the funeral of a former [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]]\n\nThe Sovereign sometimes declares other days when the Union Flag is to fly at [[half-mast]]. Half-mast means the flag is flown two-thirds of the way up the flagpole with at least the height of the flag between the top of the flag and the top of the flagpole.<ref>[http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/faqs.html#3 ''FAQ: What is half mast?''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016132137/http://www.culture.gov.uk/flagflying/faqs.html |date=16 October 2008 }} [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]]</ref>\n\n== Flying from public buildings ==\nUntil July 2007, the Union Flag was only flown on Government buildings on a limited number of special days each year. The choice of days was managed by the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] (DCMS).<ref name=\"dcms\" /> Government buildings are those used by civil servants, [[the Crown]], or the armed forces. They were not applicable to private citizens, corporations, or local authorities.<ref name=\"dcms\" />\n\nOn 3 July 2007, the [[Secretary of State for Justice|Justice Secretary]] [[Jack Straw]] laid a [[green paper]] before Parliament entitled ''The Governance of Britain''.<ref name=\"gob\" /> Alongside a range of proposed changes to the constitutional arrangements of the UK was a specific announcement that there would be consultation on whether the rules on flag-flying on Government buildings should be relaxed.\n\nTwo days later, Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] announced that with immediate effect the Union Flag would fly from the flag pole above the front entrance of [[10 Downing Street]] on every day of the year. The intention was to increase feelings of [[British national identity]]. Other Government departments were asked to follow this lead, and all Government buildings in Whitehall did so.<ref>[http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page12378.asp Morning Press Briefing] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809013048/http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page12378.asp |date=9 August 2007 }} by [[Prime Minister's Spokesman]], 6 July 2007</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/07/07/nflag107.xml Union flag already flying all year round] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' 7 July 2007</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6276280.stm Brown lifts ban on national flag] BBC News, 6 July 2007</ref><ref>[http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/news/archives/2007/07/06/brown_flies_flag_for_britain.html Brown flies flag for Britain] ''[[The Guardian]]'' 6 July 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article2034055.ece \"Union Jack will fly over No 10 permanently 'to show values'\"]. ''[[The Times]]'' 6 July 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-23403148-details/Whitehall+flies+the+flag+in+boost+for+Britishness/article.do \"Gordon orders Whitehall to fly the flag in boost for Britishness\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090819090145/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-23403148-details/Whitehall+flies+the+flag+in+boost+for+Britishness/article.do |date=19 August 2009 }} ''[[Evening Standard]]'' 6 July 2007</ref>\n\n[[James Purnell]], [[Culture Secretary]] from June 2007 to January 2008 in Brown's administration, subsequently concurred with the abolition of the restrictions \u2013 pending consultation on longer term arrangements.\n\n===Flag days===\nThe flag days directed by the DCMS include birthdays of members of the [[British Royal Family|Royal Family]], the wedding anniversary of the Monarch, [[Commonwealth Day]], [[Accession Day]], [[Coronation Day]], [[Queen's Birthday|The Queen's official birthday]], [[Remembrance Sunday]] and on the days of the [[State Opening of Parliament|State Opening]] and [[legislative session#Procedure in Commonwealth realms|prorogation]] of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]].\n\nSince the beginning of 2013, the relevant days have been:\n\n* 9 January: birthday of [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|The Duchess of Cambridge]]\n* 20 January: birthday of [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|The Countess of Wessex]]\n* 6 February: anniversary of [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]]'s accession in 1952\n* 19 February: birthday of [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|The Duke of York]]\n* Second Sunday in March: [[Commonwealth Day]]\n* 10 March: birthday of [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|The Earl of Wessex]]\n* 21 April: The Queen's birthday\n* 9 May: [[Europe Day]]\n* 2 June: anniversary of The Queen's 1953 [[Coronation Day|coronation]]\n* 10 June: birthday of [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n* A Saturday in June: [[Queen's Birthday|The Queen's Official Birthday]]\n* 21 June: birthday of [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|The Duke of Cambridge]]\n* 17 July: birthday of [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|The Duchess of Cornwall]]\n* 15 August: birthday of [[Anne, Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]]\n* Second Sunday in November: [[Remembrance Sunday]]\n* 14 November: birthday of [[Charles, Prince of Wales|The Prince of Wales]]\n* 20 November: anniversary of the wedding of The Queen and The Duke of Edinburgh\n\nIn addition, the flag should be flown in the following areas on the specified days:\n* [[Wales]] \u2013 1 March: [[Saint David's Day]]\n* [[Northern Ireland]] \u2013 17 March: [[Saint Patrick's Day]]\n* [[England]] \u2013 23 April: [[Saint George's Day]]\n* [[Scotland]] \u2013 30 November: [[Saint Andrew's Day]]\n* [[Greater London]]: The day of the opening or proroguing of Parliament\n\nSome non-central government bodies still continue to follow the flag days.\n\nIn Scotland, the [[Scottish Government]] has decreed that the [[Flag of Scotland]] (\"the Saltire\") will fly on all its buildings every day from 8&nbsp;am until sunset, but there is no specific policy on flying the Union Flag and as such it is sometimes flown alongside the Saltire and sometimes omitted. An exception is made for \"national days\". On these days, the Saltire shall be lowered and replaced with the Union Flag. These are the same as the flag days noted above with the exception of:\n* 3 September: [[Merchant Navy]] Day\n\nAnother difference is that on [[Saint Andrew's Day]], the Union Flag can only be flown if the building has more than one flagpole \u2013 the Saltire will not be lowered to make way for the Union Flag if there is only one flagpole.<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/People/royal-ceremonial \"Royal and ceremonial\"] [[Scottish Government]]</ref>\n[[File:British Airways tails lined up at LHR Terminal 5B Iwelumo.jpg|thumb|upright=1.14| The flag on British airways parked at [[London Heathrow Airport]]]]\n\n===Northern Ireland===\nIn [[Northern Ireland]], the Union Flag is flown from buildings of the [[Northern Ireland Office]] as decreed by Regulations published in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/sr/sr2000/20000347.htm |title=The Flags Regulations (Northern Ireland) 2000 |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |accessdate=2010-06-14}}</ref> The Regulations were amended in 2002 to remove the requirement to fly the flag on the birthdays of [[Queen Elizabeth, the Queen Mother]] and [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon]] who both died that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/Sr/sr2003/20030553.htm |title=The Flags Regulations (Northern Ireland) (Amendment) 2002 |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |accessdate=2010-06-14}}</ref> The current flag days are now the same as the United Kingdom government days noted above with the exception of the Duchess of Cornwall's birthday, which was only added to the UK flag days after her wedding to the Prince of Wales in 2005, and has not yet been extended to Northern Ireland.\n\nThe [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]] is the only body in the United Kingdom that is not permitted to fly the Union Flag, and is only permitted to fly its service flag or the [[Royal Standard (United Kingdom)|Royal Standard]] in the event of a visit by the Sovereign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/Sr/sr2002/20020023.htm |title=Police Emblems and Flags Regulations (Northern Ireland) 2002 |publisher=Opsi.gov.uk |accessdate=2010-06-14}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed redesigns==\n\n=== Suggested incorporation of the Welsh dragon ===\n[[File:Union Flag (including Wales).svg|thumb|One suggested redesign of the Union Jack with the red dragon from the [[flag of Wales]] added in the centre]]\nIn November 2007 the then culture minister [[Margaret Hodge]] said she would consider a redesign of the Union Flag to incorporate the [[Welsh dragon]], during a debate in the House of Commons on the frequency with which the flag flies above public buildings. The issue was initially raised by [[Ian Lucas]], another [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP, who complained that the flag introduced in 1606 following the accession of [[James VI of Scotland]] to the English throne as James I combined the cross of St George and the saltire of St Andrew. This principle continued in 1801 when the St Patrick cross was incorporated following the [[Union with Ireland Act 1800]]. Lucas claimed the identity of [[Wales]] had been suppressed ever since the [[Laws in Wales Acts 1535\u20131542]]. In the debate, [[Albert Owen]] MP said that \"we in Wales do not feel part of the union flag because the dragon or the [[Flag of Saint David|cross of St David]] is not on it.\"<ref name=guardian>Wintour, Patrick (28 November 2007). [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/nov/28/uk.britishidentity  \"Minister proposes a redesign for the union flag\"], ''The Guardian''</ref> [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP [[Stewart Jackson]] described the comments as \"eccentric\".<ref name=telegraph>Cleland, Gary (27 November 2007). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/1570613/Union-Jack-should-include-Welsh-flag-says-MP.html \"Union Jack should include Welsh flag, says MP\"], ''Daily Telegraph''</ref>\n\n=== Scottish independence ===\nAs of 2013, numerous proposals were made about how the Union Flag might be altered to create a flag for the union of England, Wales and Northern Ireland after possible [[Scottish independence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-25205017|title=What would the union jack look like if the Scottish bit was removed?|publisher=BBC News|author=Sam Judah|date=4 December 2013}}</ref> The [[College of Arms]] stated that there would be no need to change the flag in those circumstances, and the existing flag could continue to be used if desired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2013-11-26/no-plans-to-change-union-flag/|title=Union Flag: What happens if Scotland wins independence?|date=27 November 2013|publisher=ITV News}}</ref> Regarding the removal of Scottish heraldic features from the Union Flag, the [[Court of the Lord Lyon]] stated in 2012 that \"[that] would be speculation at this stage, and we could only cross that bridge if we came to it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/would-the-blue-have-to-be-taken-out-of-union-1128610|title=Would the blue have to be taken out of Union flag if Scotland became independent?|publisher=Daily Record|date=7 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Flags of the Interregnum (British Isles)#Flags of the Commonwealth|Commonwealth's flags]]\n* [[Flag Institute]]\n* [[Historical flags of the British Empire and the overseas territories]]\n* [[List of British flags|List of flags of the United Kingdom]] \u2013 a list of flags used within the United Kingdom, the Crown Dependencies and the British overseas territories.\n** [[List of English flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within England\n*** [[List of Cornish flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within [[Cornwall]]\n** [[List of Northern Irish flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within Northern Ireland\n** [[List of Scottish flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within Scotland\n** [[List of Welsh flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within Wales\n* [[List of flags of the Republic of Ireland|List of Irish flags]] \u2013 a list of flags used within the Republic of Ireland\n* [[National colours of the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Protectorate Jack]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Flags of the United Kingdom}}\n* {{FOTW|id=gb|title=United Kingdom}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130630062430/https://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/UnionJack.aspx British Monarchy \u2013 Union Flag]\n* [http://www.flaginstitute.org The Flag Institute]\n* [http://bristolgrenadiers.org/colours/colours.htm British Armed forces Grenadiers Colour]\n\n{{-}}\n{{UKFlags}}\n{{Flag of Europe}}\n{{Union Flag}}\n\n[[Category:Flags of the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:National flags|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:National symbols of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Unionism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Flags with crosses|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Flags introduced in 1801|United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "2600:6c5d:5b80:2416:7196:ba09:aed4:e03f", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSt Patrick's saltire)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flag_of_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "Bernie Clifton", "text_new": "{{short description|British comedian and entertainer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bernie Clifton\n| occupation = Entertainer\n| birth_name = Bernard M Quinn\n| birth_date = 30 April 1936\n| birth_place = [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], [[Lancashire]], England\n}}\n\n'''Bernie M Clifton''' (born '''Bernard Quinn''')<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton auditions on The Voice |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35271062 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=9 January 2016}}</ref> is a British comedian and entertainer, known best for his work with his orange [[ostrich]] puppet costume Oswald the Ostrich.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/>\n\n==Career==\nClifton's first performing job was as a singer with a dance band, however he was fired after a month.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/> His first television performance was on the light entertainment show ''[[The Good Old Days (British TV series)|The Good Old Days]]'', where he was inspired by [[Les Dawson]].<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/>\n\nHe performed in the 1979 ''[[Royal Variety Performance]]''.<ref name=WardJan2016>{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Rachel |title=Bernie Clifton moves Ricky Wilson to tears after surprise performance on The Voice |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/the-voice/12091640/Bernie-Clifton-surprise-appearance-The-Voice-ricky-wilson.html |work=The Telegraph |date=10 January 2016 |language=en}}</ref> Since then he has performed in it several times, including 2016.<ref name=LawrenceDec2016>{{cite news |last1=Lawrence |first1=Ben |title=Is the Royal Variety Performance still fit for a king (or queen)? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/12/13/royal-variety-performance-still-fit-king-queen/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was a regular appearance on ''[[Crackerjack! (TV series)|Crackerjack!]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Anita |title=Crackerjack makes a comeback: BBC revives children's show for a new generation |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/02/11/crackerjack-makes-comeback-bbc-revives-retro-kids-show-new-generation/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=11 February 2019}}</ref> During the 1980s, he appeared on ''[[The Keith Harris Show]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Anita |title=Keith Harris, Orville ventriloquist, dies at 67 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/11567842/Keith-Harris-Orville-ventriloquist-dies-at-67.html |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=28 April 2015}}</ref> and in 1982, Clifton ran the [[London Marathon]] with Oswald the Ostrich.<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/>\n\nIn 2002, Clifton featured on the BBC2 documentary series ''The Entertainers'', which followed 1970s and 80s entertainers who had dropped out of the limelight.<ref name=SmithSep2002>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Rupert |title=A generation of TV veterans are back |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/sep/16/broadcasting.tvandradio |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=16 September 2002}}</ref> In 2005, Clifton and Oswald appeared in the music video for [[Peter Kay]] and [[Tony Christie]]'s [[Comic Relief]] version of \"[[(Is This the Way to) Amarillo]]\".<ref name=WardJan2016/>\n\nIn 2005 Clifton appeared as himself in an episode of the [[David Renwick]] sitcom [[Love Soup]] after previously being mentioned by Renwick in an early episode of [[One Foot in the Grave]].<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0636925/reference</ref>\n\nHe made his [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] debut in 2006 at the Udderbelly venue. Writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', Brian Logan gave it 3 out of 5 stars and called it an \"exercise in retro comedy\", but \"also unrepentantly funny\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Logan |first1=Brian |title=Bernie Clifton, Udderbelly, Edinburgh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/aug/17/comedy.edinburgh20061 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=17 August 2006}}</ref>\n\nClifton was a contestant on [[The Voice UK (series 5)|Series 5]] of ''[[The Voice UK]]'', applying under his birth name. He performed \"[[The Impossible Dream (The Quest)]]\" from ''[[Man of La Mancha]]'', and did not advance past the blind auditions.<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/> Following his appearance on the show he released an album of covers called ''The Impossible Dream'', which included \"[[The Lady in Red (Chris de Burgh song)|The Lady in Red]]\" and \"[[Wind Beneath My Wings]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton in death metal mix-up |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-36129559 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=25 April 2016}}</ref> After a death metal band's song titles were printed on his album cover by mistake, Clifton presented an award at the [[Kerrang! Awards|''Kerrang!'' Awards]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton to go to Kerrang! Awards |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-36378371 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he starred in [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]'s ''Last Laugh in Vegas'', a documentary following eight \"showbiz legends\" as they prepare a show in [[Las Vegas]].<ref name=LastLaugh>{{cite web |title=Last Laugh In Vegas - ITV Factual |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/last_laugh_in_vegas/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |website=British Comedy Guide}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Clifton appeared as a guest on the first episode of the new series of ''Crackerjack!'' on [[CBBC]].<ref name=CBBC2020>{{cite web |title=CBBC - Crackerjack!, Series 1, One |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000ddhl |accessdate=4 March 2020 |website=BBC}}</ref> In February, he played himself in the first episode of ''Meet The Richardsons'' on [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]].<ref name=RichardsonsEp1>{{cite news |last1=Guide |first1=British Comedy |title=Meet The Richardsons Series 1, Episode 1 |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/meet_the_richardsons/episodes/1/1/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=British Comedy Guide}}</ref> Within the episode, he is a family friend of [[Jon Richardson]] and teaches him how to operate a monkey puppet similar to his ostrich.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Young |first1=Lottie |title=Meet The Richardsons offers a peek into the life of a comedy couple |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/meet-the-richardsons-review-a4373506.html |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=27 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nClifton has starred in several [[pantomimes]], playing the father of [[Cinderella]] at the [[Hull New Theatre]] in 2018 and at [[Northampton]]'s [[Royal & Derngate]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wiser |first1=Danny |title=Pantomime starring Anita Dobson criticised as 'sexist and lewd' as audience walk out during show |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/12/23/pantomime-starring-anita-dobson-criticised-sexist-lewd-audience/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=23 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mooney |first1=Lauren |title=Cinderella review at Royal and Derngate, Northampton |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2019/cinderella-anita-dobson-bernie-clifton-review-at-royal-and-derngate-northampton/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Stage |date=11 December 2019}}</ref> He has also presented various shows on [[BBC Radio Sheffield]],<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Radio Sheffield - Live-ish, 23/03/2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p072qk3z |website=BBC |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Radio Sheffield - BBC Radio Sheffield Special, The Golden Days of Working Men's Clubs |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02r9fzy |website=BBC |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> and [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hepworth |first1=David |title=Next week's radio: from Richard Tauber Revived to Studio 360 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/oct/26/david-hepworth-radio-review |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=26 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Daoust |first1=Phil |title=Radio pick of the day: The Material World {{!}} Under the Skin {{!}} The Pallisers |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/dec/28/tvandradio.radio |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=28 December 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nClifton was born on 30 April 1936 in [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], Lancashire where he also grew up.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017>{{cite news |last1=Jamieson |first1=Georgy |title=Bernie Clifton interview |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/people/bernie_clifton/features/2017_interview/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=British Comedy Guide |date=16 September 2017}}</ref><ref>https://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/districts.pl?r=172731578:7272&d=bmd_1586250123</ref><ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1101543/bio?ref_=nm_ql_1</ref>\n\nIn 1961 Clifton married Marjorie Hancock, they went on to have four children together. Clifton was widowed in 2000.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1101543/bio?ref_=nm_ql_1</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|1979\n|''Royal Variety Performance''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=WardJan2016/>\n|-\n|2002\n|''The Entertainers''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=SmithSep2002/>\n|-\n|2005\n|''Love Soup''\n|Himself\n|series 1 episode 4\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[The Voice UK]]''\n|Himself\n|[[The Voice UK (series 5)|series 5]], episode 1\n|<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/><ref name=WardJan2016/>\n|-\n|2016\n|''Royal Variety Performance''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=LawrenceDec2016/>\n|-\n|2018\n|''Last Laugh in Vegas''\n|Himself\n|5 episodes\n|<ref name=LastLaugh/>\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Crackerjack! (TV series)|Crackerjack!]]''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|<ref name=CBBC2020/>\n|-\n|2020\n|''Meet The Richardsons''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|<ref name=RichardsonsEp1/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1101543|name=Bernie Clifton}}\n*[http://www.bernieclifton.co.uk/ Website]\n\n{{The Voice UK}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clifton, Bernie}}\n[[Category:British comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from St Helens, Merseyside]]\n\n{{UK-comedian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British comedian and entertainer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bernie Clifton\n| occupation = Entertainer\n| birth_name = Bernard Quinn\n| birth_date =  {{Birth year and age|1936|04}}\n| birth_place = [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], [[Lancashire]], England\n}}\n\n'''Bernie Clifton''' (born '''Bernard Quinn''')<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton auditions on The Voice |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35271062 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=9 January 2016}}</ref> is a British comedian and entertainer, known best for his work with his orange [[ostrich]] puppet costume Oswald the Ostrich.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/>\n\n==Early life==\nClifton grew up in [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], Lancashire.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017>{{cite news |last1=Jamieson |first1=Georgy |title=Bernie Clifton interview |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/people/bernie_clifton/features/2017_interview/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=British Comedy Guide |date=16 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nClifton's first performing job was as a singer with a dance band, however he was fired after a month.<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/> His first television performance was on the light entertainment show ''[[The Good Old Days (British TV series)|The Good Old Days]]'', where he was inspired by [[Les Dawson]].<ref name=JamiesonSep2017/>\n\nHe performed in the 1979 ''[[Royal Variety Performance]]''.<ref name=WardJan2016>{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Rachel |title=Bernie Clifton moves Ricky Wilson to tears after surprise performance on The Voice |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/the-voice/12091640/Bernie-Clifton-surprise-appearance-The-Voice-ricky-wilson.html |work=The Telegraph |date=10 January 2016 |language=en}}</ref> Since then he has performed in it several times, including 2016.<ref name=LawrenceDec2016>{{cite news |last1=Lawrence |first1=Ben |title=Is the Royal Variety Performance still fit for a king (or queen)? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/12/13/royal-variety-performance-still-fit-king-queen/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was a regular appearance on ''[[Crackerjack! (TV series)|Crackerjack!]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Anita |title=Crackerjack makes a comeback: BBC revives children's show for a new generation |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/02/11/crackerjack-makes-comeback-bbc-revives-retro-kids-show-new-generation/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=11 February 2019}}</ref> During the 1980s, he appeared on ''[[The Keith Harris Show]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Anita |title=Keith Harris, Orville ventriloquist, dies at 67 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/11567842/Keith-Harris-Orville-ventriloquist-dies-at-67.html |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=28 April 2015}}</ref> and in 1982, Clifton ran the [[London Marathon]] with Oswald the Ostrich.<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/>\n\nIn 2002, Clifton featured on the BBC2 documentary series ''The Entertainers'', which followed 1970s and 80s entertainers who had dropped out of the limelight.<ref name=SmithSep2002>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Rupert |title=A generation of TV veterans are back |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/sep/16/broadcasting.tvandradio |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=16 September 2002}}</ref> In 2005, Clifton and Oswald appeared in the music video for [[Peter Kay]] and [[Tony Christie]]'s [[Comic Relief]] version of \"[[(Is This the Way to) Amarillo]]\".<ref name=WardJan2016/> \n\nHe made his [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] debut in 2006 at the Udderbelly venue. Writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', Brian Logan gave it 3 out of 5 stars and called it an \"exercise in retro comedy\", but \"also unrepentantly funny\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Logan |first1=Brian |title=Bernie Clifton, Udderbelly, Edinburgh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/aug/17/comedy.edinburgh20061 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=17 August 2006}}</ref>\n\nClifton was a contestant on [[The Voice UK (series 5)|Series 5]] of ''[[The Voice UK]]'', applying under his birth name. He performed \"[[The Impossible Dream (The Quest)]]\" from ''[[Man of La Mancha]]'', and did not advance past the blind auditions.<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/> Following his appearance on the show he released an album of covers called ''The Impossible Dream'', which included \"[[The Lady in Red (Chris de Burgh song)|The Lady in Red]]\" and \"[[Wind Beneath My Wings]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton in death metal mix-up |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-36129559 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=25 April 2016}}</ref> After a death metal band's song titles were printed on his album cover by mistake, Clifton presented an award at the [[Kerrang! Awards|''Kerrang!'' Awards]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bernie Clifton to go to Kerrang! Awards |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-36378371 |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he starred in [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]'s ''Last Laugh in Vegas'', a documentary following eight \"showbiz legends\" as they prepare a show in [[Las Vegas]].<ref name=LastLaugh>{{cite web |title=Last Laugh In Vegas - ITV Factual |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/last_laugh_in_vegas/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |website=British Comedy Guide}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Clifton appeared as a guest on the first episode of the new series of ''Crackerjack!'' on [[CBBC]].<ref name=CBBC2020>{{cite web |title=CBBC - Crackerjack!, Series 1, One |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000ddhl |accessdate=4 March 2020 |website=BBC}}</ref> In February, he played himself in the first episode of ''Meet The Richardsons'' on [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]].<ref name=RichardsonsEp1>{{cite news |last1=Guide |first1=British Comedy |title=Meet The Richardsons Series 1, Episode 1 |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/meet_the_richardsons/episodes/1/1/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=British Comedy Guide}}</ref> Within the episode, he is a family friend of [[Jon Richardson]] and teaches him how to operate a monkey puppet similar to his ostrich.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Young |first1=Lottie |title=Meet The Richardsons offers a peek into the life of a comedy couple |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/meet-the-richardsons-review-a4373506.html |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=27 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nClifton has starred in several [[pantomimes]], playing the father of [[Cinderella]] at the [[Hull New Theatre]] in 2018 and at [[Northampton]]'s [[Royal & Derngate]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wiser |first1=Danny |title=Pantomime starring Anita Dobson criticised as 'sexist and lewd' as audience walk out during show |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/12/23/pantomime-starring-anita-dobson-criticised-sexist-lewd-audience/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=23 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mooney |first1=Lauren |title=Cinderella review at Royal and Derngate, Northampton |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2019/cinderella-anita-dobson-bernie-clifton-review-at-royal-and-derngate-northampton/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Stage |date=11 December 2019}}</ref> He has also presented various shows on [[BBC Radio Sheffield]],<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Radio Sheffield - Live-ish, 23/03/2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p072qk3z |website=BBC |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Radio Sheffield - BBC Radio Sheffield Special, The Golden Days of Working Men's Clubs |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02r9fzy |website=BBC |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> and [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hepworth |first1=David |title=Next week's radio: from Richard Tauber Revived to Studio 360 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/oct/26/david-hepworth-radio-review |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=26 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Daoust |first1=Phil |title=Radio pick of the day: The Material World {{!}} Under the Skin {{!}} The Pallisers |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/dec/28/tvandradio.radio |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=28 December 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|1979\n|''Royal Variety Performance''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=WardJan2016/>\n|-\n|2002\n|''The Entertainers''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=SmithSep2002/>\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[The Voice UK]]''\n|Himself\n|[[The Voice UK (series 5)|Series 5]], episode 1\n|<ref name=BBCNewsJan2016/><ref name=WardJan2016/>\n|-\n|2016\n|''Royal Variety Performance''\n|Himself\n|\n|<ref name=LawrenceDec2016/>\n|-\n|2018\n|''Last Laugh in Vegas''\n|Himself\n|5 episodes\n|<ref name=LastLaugh/>\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Crackerjack! (TV series)|Crackerjack!]]''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|<ref name=CBBC2020/>\n|-\n|2020\n|''Meet The Richardsons''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|<ref name=RichardsonsEp1/>\n|}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=1101543|name=Bernie Clifton}}\n* [http://www.bernieclifton.co.uk/ Website]\n\n{{The Voice UK}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clifton, Bernie}}\n[[Category:British comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from St Helens, Merseyside]]\n\n{{UK-comedian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "International-Ice", "label": "safe", "comment": "rvv", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernie_Clifton"}
{"title_page": "Arnold Krupat", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2011}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=June 2011}}\n}}\n\n'''Arnold Krupat, Ph.D.''' (born 1941) is an American author and Professor of Literature at [[Sarah Lawrence College]] in [[Bronxville, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://books.wwnorton.com/books/Author.aspx?id=4634 |title=Arnold Krupat &#124; W. W. Norton & Company |publisher=Books.wwnorton.com |date= |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> His work has been published in ''Nineteenth-Century Fiction'', ''The Quest'', and ''Sarah Lawrence Journal''.<ref>Donaldson, Scott; and Kerouac, Jack. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=VesrAQAAIAAJ&q=%22arnold+krupat%22&dq=%22arnold+krupat%22&hl=en&ei=nyv6TdbTJeXOiAKAvpmEBQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBzgK On the road''], Viking Press, page 397, 1979. {{ISBN|978-0-670-52513-3}}</ref> He is a recipient of six fellowships from the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], and has also held a Fulbright Fellowship, an Woodrow Wilson Fellowship, and a Guggenheim Fellowship.\n\n== Personal background ==\nKrupat was born in 1941 in the [[Bronx, New York]] and grew up in the [[Jacob Riis]] Housing Projects on the lower east side of [[Manhattan]]. He went to public grade school and then to [[Stuyvesant High School]], from which he graduated in 1958.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nHe attended [[New York University]]'s [[New York University#Washington Square campus|Washington Square College of Arts and Science]] on [[scholarship]], earning his [[Bachelor's degree]] [[summa cum laude]] and [[Phi Beta Kappa]] in 1962. From 1962 to 1963, he spent a year at the [[Universite de Strasbourg]] on a [[Fulbright Fellowship]]. After returning to New York, he entered graduate school at [[Columbia University]] on a [[Woodrow Wilson National Fellowship Foundation#The national Woodrow Wilson Fellowship (1957\u20131974)|Woodrow Wilson Foundation Fellowship]]. He received his [[Ph.D]] from Columbia with honors in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/honors.php |title=Arnold Krupat \u2013 Global Studies \u2013 Sarah Lawrence College |publisher=Pages.slc.edu |accessdate=June 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727193646/http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/honors.php |archivedate=July 27, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/education.php |title=Arnold Krupat \u2013 Global Studies \u2013 Sarah Lawrence College |publisher=Pages.slc.edu |accessdate=June 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727193750/http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/education.php |archivedate=July 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n;Family\nIn 1962, Krupat married Kitty Weiss; the couple divorced in 1966.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nIn 1968, he married Cynthia Muser. While the couple divorced in 1993, together, they had two children. Their daughter, Tanya, is a social  worker with the [[Osborne Association]] in New York, and lives in Brooklyn with her son, Arlo Krupat. Their son, Jeremy, is a Professor at the Business School at Cambridge University (UK).\n\nIn 2007, Krupat married Andrea Ferster, a  lawyer in [[Washington, D.C.]] They were divorced in 2012. He lives in [[Hastings-on-Hudson, New York]].{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n== Professional background ==\n;Academic work\nFrom 1965 to 1968, Krupat taught in the English Department at [[Rutgers University]] in [[New Brunswick, New Jersey]]. He started teaching at Sarah Lawrence College in Bronxville, New York in 1968. He retired in June 2012.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n;Writing\nWhile teaching at Sarah Lawrence, Krupat developed an interest in [[critical theory]] and [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] literature. His first book, ''For Those Who Come After: a Study of Native American Autobiography'', was published in 1985. A second edition, with a foreword by Paul John Eakin, appeared in 1987.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nIn 1989, he published a novel, ''Woodsmen, or Thoreau & the Indians'', and in 2012 What-to-do? a novel. He has also authored, edited, or co-edited 12 more books. Scheduled for release in 2012, his latest academic work is entitled ''That the People Might Live: a Theory of Native American Elegy''.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nHe is the author of ''Ethnocriticism: Ethnography, History, Literature''; ''The Voice in the Margin: Native American Literature and the Canon''; and ''Red Matters''. In 2007, he wrote ''All That Remains: Native Studies''. His \"Changed Forever: American Indian Boarding-School Literature,\" volume 1 appeared in 2018. A second volume is forthcoming. He was the editor of a number of anthologies, including ''Native American Autobiography: An Anthology and New Voices in Native American Literary Criticism''.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nIn 2001, he edited ''Here First: Autobiographical Essays by Native American Writers'', with Brian Swann. The work was honored with the [[Wordcraft Circle of Native Writers and Storytellers Award]] for best book of nonfiction prose.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nKrupat has contributed chapters to edited books, and his essays have appeared in the major professional journals. He has been the editor for Native American literature for the ''[[The Norton Anthology of American Literature|Norton Anthology of American Literature]]'' from its 5th to its  8th edition. He has presented talks at colleges and universities throughout the United States as well as in Brazil, Cyprus, England, France, Germany, Hungary, Italy, Norway, Sweden, and Wales.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n== Fellowships ==\nKrupat is a recipient of six fellowships from the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]]. In 2007, he was the recipient of the Sarah Lawrence Excellence in Teaching Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/ |title=Arnold Krupat \u2013 Global Studies \u2013 Sarah Lawrence College |publisher=Pages.slc.edu |accessdate=June 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727193829/http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/ |archivedate=July 27, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n* 1962: Fulbright Fellowship\n* 1963: Woodrow Wilson Foundation Fellowship\n* 2005: Guggenheim Fellowship<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/8216-arnold-krupat |title=Arnold Krupat \u2013 John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation |publisher=Gf.org |date= |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slc.edu/magazine/philanthropy/fac-ppp.php |title=Sarah Lawrence Magazine: The Power of Giving \u2013 Published, Performed, Presented |publisher=Slc.edu |accessdate=June 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204202518/http://www.slc.edu/magazine/philanthropy/fac-ppp.php |archivedate=December 4, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Published works ==\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''For Those Who Come After: A Study of Native American Autobiography'', University of California Press, 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-520-06606-9}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''The Voice in the Margin: Native American Literature and the Canon'', University of California Press, 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-520-06669-4}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''Ethnocriticism: Ethnography, History, Literature'', University of California Press, 1992. {{ISBN|978-0-520-07666-2}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''Woodsmen, or Thoreau and the Indians'', University of Oklahoma Press, 1994. {{ISBN|978-0-8061-2671-5}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''The Turn to the Native: Studies in Criticism and Culture'', Bison Books, 1998. {{ISBN|0-8032-7786-5}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''Red Matters: Native American Studies (Rethinking the Americas)'', University of Pennsylvania Press, 2002. {{ISBN|978-0-8122-1803-9}}\n* Baym, Nina; Franklin, Wayne; Gura, Philip F.; Krupat, Arnold; and Levine, Robert S. (editors). ''Norton Anthology of American Literature'', New York: W.W. Norton and Co., 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-393-92993-5}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''All That Remains: Varieties of Indigenous Expression '', University of Nebraska Press, 2009. {{ISBN|978-0-8032-1890-1}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''That the People Might Live: Loss and Renewal in Native American Elegy'', Cornell University Press, 2012.\nKrupat, Arnold, ed. \"Companion to James Welch's The Heartsong of Charging Elk.\" University of Nebraska Press, 2015.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110727193829/http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/ Arnold Krupat] at [[Sarah Lawrence College]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krupat, Arnold}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College faculty]]\n[[Category:American literary theorists]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Stuyvesant High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2011}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=June 2011}}\n}}\n\n'''Arnold Krupat, Ph.D.''' (born 1941) is an American author and Professor of Literature at [[Sarah Lawrence College]] in [[Bronxville, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://books.wwnorton.com/books/Author.aspx?id=4634 |title=Arnold Krupat &#124; W. W. Norton & Company |publisher=Books.wwnorton.com |date= |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> His work has been published in ''Nineteenth-Century Fiction'', ''The Quest'', and ''Sarah Lawrence Journal''.<ref>Donaldson, Scott; and Kerouac, Jack. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=VesrAQAAIAAJ&q=%22arnold+krupat%22&dq=%22arnold+krupat%22&hl=en&ei=nyv6TdbTJeXOiAKAvpmEBQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBzgK On the road''], Viking Press, page 397, 1979. {{ISBN|978-0-670-52513-3}}</ref> He is a recipient of six fellowships from the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], and has also held a Fulbright Fellowship, an Woodrow Wilson Fellowship, and a Guggenheim Fellowship.\n\n== Personal background ==\nKrupat was born in 1941 in the [[Bronx, New York]] and grew up in the [[Jacob Riis]] Housing Projects on the lower east side of [[Manhattan]]. He went to public grade school and then to [[Stuyvesant High School]], from which he graduated in 1958.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nHe attended [[New York University]]'s [[New York University#Washington Square campus|Washington Square College of Arts and Science]] on [[scholarship]], earning his [[Bachelor's degree]] [[summa cum laude]] and [[Phi Beta Kappa]] in 1962. From 1962 to 1963, he spent a year at the [[Universite de Strasbourg]] on a [[Fulbright Fellowship]]. After returning to New York, he entered graduate school at [[Columbia University]] on a [[Woodrow Wilson National Fellowship Foundation#The national Woodrow Wilson Fellowship (1957\u20131974)|Woodrow Wilson Foundation Fellowship]]. He received his [[Ph.D]] from Columbia with honors in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/honors.php |title=Arnold Krupat \u2013 Global Studies \u2013 Sarah Lawrence College |publisher=Pages.slc.edu |accessdate=June 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727193646/http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/honors.php |archivedate=July 27, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/education.php |title=Arnold Krupat \u2013 Global Studies \u2013 Sarah Lawrence College |publisher=Pages.slc.edu |accessdate=June 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727193750/http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/education.php |archivedate=July 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n;Family\nIn 1962, Krupat married Kitty Weiss; the couple divorced in 1966.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nIn 1968, he married Cynthia Muser. While the couple divorced in 1993, together, they had two children. Their daughter, Tanya, is a social  worker with the [[Osborne Association]] in New York, and lives in Brooklyn with her son, Arlo Krupat. Their son, Jeremy, is a Professor at the Business School at Cambridge University (UK).\n\nIn 2007, Krupat married Andrea Ferster, a  lawyer in [[Washington, D.C.]] They were divorced in 2012. He lives in [[Hastings-on-Hudson, New York]].{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n== Professional background ==\n;Academic work\nFrom 1965 to 1968, Krupat taught in the English Department at [[Rutgers University]] in [[New Brunswick, New Jersey]]. He started teaching at Sarah Lawrence College in Bronxville, New York in 1968. He retired in June 2012.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n;Writing\nWhile teaching at Sarah Lawrence, Krupat developed an interest in [[critical theory]] and [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] literature. His first book, ''For Those Who Come After: a Study of Native American Autobiography'', was published in 1985. A second edition, with a foreword by Paul John Eakin, appeared in 1987.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nIn 1989, he published a novel, ''Woodsmen, or Thoreau & the Indians'', and in 2012 What-to-do? a novel. He has also authored, edited, or co-edited 12 more books. Scheduled for release in 2012, his latest academic work is entitled ''That the People Might Live: a Theory of Native American Elegy''.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nHe is the author of ''Ethnocriticism: Ethnography, History, Literature''; ''The Voice in the Margin: Native American Literature and the Canon''; and ''Red Matters''. In 2007, he wrote ''All That Remains: Native Studies''. His \"Changed Forever: American Indian Boarding-School Literature,\" volume 1 appeared in 2018. A second volume is forthcoming. He was the editor of a number of anthologies, including ''Native American Autobiography: An Anthology and New Voices in Native American Literary Criticism''.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nIn 2001, he edited ''Here First: Autobiographical Essays by Native American Writers'', with Brian Swann. The work was honored with the [[Wordcraft Circle of Native Writers and Storytellers Award]] for best book of nonfiction prose.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nKrupat has contributed chapters to edited books, and his essays have appeared in the major professional journals. He has been the editor for Native American literature for the ''[[The Norton Anthology of American Literature|Norton Anthology of American Literature]]'' from its 5th to its  8th edition. He has presented talks at colleges and universities throughout the United States as well as in Brazil, Cyprus, England, France, Germany, Hungary, Italy, Norway, Sweden, and Wales.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n== Fellowships ==\nKrupat is a recipient of six fellowships from the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]]. In 2007, he was the recipient of the Sarah Lawrence Excellence in Teaching Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/ |title=Arnold Krupat \u2013 Global Studies \u2013 Sarah Lawrence College |publisher=Pages.slc.edu |accessdate=June 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727193829/http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/ |archivedate=July 27, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n* 1962: Fulbright Fellowship\n* 1963: Woodrow Wilson Foundation Fellowship\n* 2005: Guggenheim Fellowship<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/8216-arnold-krupat |title=Arnold Krupat \u2013 John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation |publisher=Gf.org |date= |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slc.edu/magazine/philanthropy/fac-ppp.php |title=Sarah Lawrence Magazine: The Power of Giving \u2013 Published, Performed, Presented |publisher=Slc.edu |accessdate=June 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204202518/http://www.slc.edu/magazine/philanthropy/fac-ppp.php |archivedate=December 4, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Published works ==\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''For Those Who Come After: A Study of Native American Autobiography'', University of California Press, 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-520-06606-9}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''The Voice in the Margin: Native American Literature and the Canon'', University of California Press, 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-520-06669-4}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''Ethnocriticism: Ethnography, History, Literature'', University of California Press, 1992. {{ISBN|978-0-520-07666-2}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''Woodsmen, or Thoreau and the Indians'', University of Oklahoma Press, 1994. {{ISBN|978-0-8061-2671-5}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''The Turn to the Native: Studies in Criticism and Culture'', Bison Books, 1998. {{ISBN|0-8032-7786-5}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''Red Matters: Native American Studies (Rethinking the Americas)'', University of Pennsylvania Press, 2002. {{ISBN|978-0-8122-1803-9}}\n* Baym, Nina; Franklin, Wayne; Gura, Philip F.; Krupat, Arnold; and Levine, Robert S. (editors). ''Norton Anthology of American Literature'', New York: W.W. Norton and Co., 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-393-92993-5}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''All That Remains: Varieties of Indigenous Expression '', University of Nebraska Press, 2009. {{ISBN|978-0-8032-1890-1}}\n* Krupat, Arnold. ''That the People Might Live: Loss and Renewal in Native American Elegy'', Cornell University Press, 2012.\nKrupat, Arnold, ed. \"Companion to James Welch's The Heartsong of Charging Elk.\" University of Nebraska Press, 2015.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110727193829/http://pages.slc.edu/~akrupat/ Arnold Krupat] at [[Sarah Lawrence College]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krupat, Arnold}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College faculty]]\n[[Category:American literary theorists]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Stuyvesant High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "